{"title_page": "History of USDA nutrition guides", "text_new": "The history of [[USDA]] nutrition guides includes over 100 years of American [[nutrition]] advice.  The guides have been updated over time, to adopt new scientific findings and new public health marketing techniques. The current guidelines are the [[Dietary Guidelines for Americans]] 2015 - 2020. Over time they have described from 4 to 11 [[food groups]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Nestle, Marion|title=Food Politics: How the Food Industry Influences Nutrition and Health|year=2013|origyear=2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-27596-6|pages=36\u201337}}</ref> Various guides have been criticized as not accurately representing scientific information about optimal nutrition, and as being overly influenced by the agricultural industries the USDA promotes.\n\n== Earliest guides ==\nThe USDA's first nutrition guidelines were published in 1894 by Dr. [[Wilbur Olin Atwater]] as a farmers' bulletin.<ref name=USDAHistory>{{cite web|title=Dietary Recommendations and How They Have Changed Over Time|url=https://www.ers.usda.gov/webdocs/publications/42215/5831_aib750b_1_.pdf|work=America's Eating Habits: Changes and Consequences|publisher=United States Department of Agriculture|accessdate=2 June 2011|format=PDF|date=May 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/CAT87201446 |title=Farmers' Bulletin No. 23 - Foods : Nutritive Value and Cost |last=Atwater |first=W.O. |year=1894 |website=Internet Archive |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=United States Department of Agriculture}}</ref> In Atwater's 1904 publication titled ''Principles of Nutrition and Nutritive Value of Food,'' he advocated variety, proportionality and moderation; measuring [[food energy|calories]]; and an efficient, affordable diet that focused on nutrient-rich foods and less fat, sugar and [[starch]].<ref>{{cite web|title=USDA Food Pyramid History|url=http://www.healthy-eating-politics.com/usda-food-pyramid.html|work=Healthy Eating Politics|accessdate=2 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228122702/http://www.healthy-eating-politics.com/usda-food-pyramid.html|archive-date=28 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Principles of Nutrition and Nutritive Value of Food|url=https://archive.org/stream/principlesofnutr00atwa|work=Internet Archive|accessdate=2 June 2011}}</ref> This information preceded the discovery of individual [[vitamin]]s beginning in 1910.\n\nA new guide in 1916, ''Food for Young Children'' by nutritionist Caroline Hunt, categorized foods into milk and meat; cereals; vegetables and fruits; fats and fatty foods; and sugars and sugary foods. ''How to Select Food'' in 1917 promoted these five food groups to adults, and the guidelines remained in place through the 1920s. In 1933, the USDA introduced food plans at four different cost levels in response to the [[Great Depression]].<ref name=USDAHistory/>\n\nIn 1941, the first [[Dietary Reference Intake|Recommended Dietary Allowances]] were created, listing specific intakes for [[food energy|calories]], [[protein (nutrient)|protein]], [[iron deficiency (medicine)|iron]], [[calcium#Nutrition|calcium]], and vitamins [[vitamin A|A]], [[thiamine|B<sub>1</sub>]], [[riboflavin|B<sub>2</sub>]] [[niacin|B<sub>3</sub>]], [[vitamin C|C]] and [[vitamin D|D]].<ref name=USDAHistory/>\n\n== Basic 7 ==\n[[File:USDA_-_Basic_7_Food_Groups.jpg|thumb|The USDA's \"Basic 7\" food groups from 1943 to 1956.]]\nIn 1943, during [[World War II]], The USDA introduced a [[nutrition guide]] promoting the \"Basic 7\" [[food group]]s to help maintain nutritional standards under wartime [[Rationing#United States|food rationing]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Food Demonstrations To Be Held Over Nation|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=b9U-AAAAIBAJ&pg=6605,3660154|accessdate=2 June 2011|newspaper=The Tuscaloosa News|date=2 April 1943|agency=The Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=To Demonstrate \"Basic 7\" Diet|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qXNhAAAAIBAJ&pg=4981,1684677|accessdate=2 June 2011|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|date=2 April 1943|agency=The Associated Press|location=Fredericksburg, Virginia}}</ref> The Basic 7 food groups were:\n\n# Green and yellow vegetables (some raw; some cooked, frozen or canned)\n# Oranges, tomatoes, [[grapefruit]] (or raw [[cabbage]] or [[leaf vegetable|salad greens]])\n# Potatoes and other vegetables and fruits (raw, dried, cooked, frozen or canned)\n# Milk and milk products (fluid, [[evaporated milk|evaporated]], [[powdered milk|dried milk]], or cheese)\n# Meat, poultry, [[fish (food)|fish]], or [[egg (food)|eggs]] (or dried [[bean]]s, [[pea]]s, [[nut (fruit)|nuts]], or [[peanut butter]])\n# Bread, flour, and cereals (natural [[whole grain]], or [[enriched flour|enriched]] or restored)\n# Butter and [[food fortification|fortified]] [[margarine]] (with added Vitamin A)\n\n== Basic Four ==\nFrom 1956 until 1992 the United States Department of Agriculture recommended its \"Basic Four\" food groups.<ref name=\"Basic4\">{{cite web|url=https://lifestox.com/top-5-foods-highest-in-fiber/|title=Foods high in fiber|last=|first=|date=|work=Life Stox|publisher=lifestox|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>{{dead link|date=January 2020|url=https://lifestox.com/top-5-foods-highest-in-fiber/}} These food groups were:\n\n* Vegetables and fruits: Recommended as excellent sources of vitamins C and A, and a good source of [[fiber]]. Four or more servings from this group were recommended daily. Previous USDA food guides showed vegetables and fruits as unique groups, each with at least two recommended servings per day.\n* Milk: Recommended as a good source of calcium, [[phosphorus]], protein, riboflavin, and sometimes vitamins A and D. Cheese, [[ice cream]], and [[ice milk]] could sometimes replace milk. Four servings from this group for teens and two for adults were recommended as a minimum daily.\n* Meat: Two daily servings at least were recommended for protein, iron and certain [[B vitamins]]. Includes meat, poultry, fish, eggs, dry beans, dry peas, and peanut butter.\n* Cereals and breads: Whole grain and enriched breads were especially recommended as good sources of iron, B vitamins and [[carbohydrate]]s, as well as sources of protein and fiber. Includes cereals, breads, [[cornmeal]], [[macaroni]], [[noodle]]s, rice and [[spaghetti]]. With the Basic Four daily food guide, the recommended minimum daily servings for the grains group doubled from two to four. Previously, in the Basic Seven guide, refined and non-enriched grains were included along with solid fats and sugar in a cluster of foods outside the essential seven.\n\n\"Other foods\" were said to round out meals and satisfy appetites. These included additional servings from the Basic Four, or foods such as butter, margarine, [[salad dressing]] and [[cooking oil]], [[sauce]]s, [[Fruit preserves|jellies]] and [[syrup]]s.<ref name=Basic4/>\n\nThe Basic Four guide was omnipresent in nutrition [[education in the United States]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Haddix|first=Carol|title=Four basic food groups grow up with the times|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=negLAAAAIBAJ&pg=6552,2002584|accessdate=12 June 2011|newspaper=Evening Independent|date=24 July 1985|agency=Chicago Tribune|location=St. Petersburg, Florida}}</ref> A notable example is the 1972 series [[Mulligan Stew (TV series)|Mulligan Stew]], providing nutrition education for schoolchildren in reruns until 1981.\n\n== Food Guide Pyramid ==\n[[File:USDA Food Pyramid.gif|thumb|The USDA's 1992 [[food guide pyramid]].]]\n{{main|Food Guide Pyramid}}\nThe introduction of the USDA's [[food guide pyramid]] in 1992 attempted to express the recommended servings of each food group, which previous guides did not do. 6 to 11 servings of bread, cereal, rice and pasta occupied the large base of the pyramid; followed by 3 to 5 servings of vegetables; then fruits (2 to 4); then milk, yogurt and cheese (2 to 3); followed by meat, poultry, fish, dry beans, eggs, and nuts (2 to 3); and finally fats, oils and sweets in the small apex (to be used sparingly). Inside each group were several images of representative foods, as well as symbols representing the fat and sugar contents of the foods.<ref>{{cite news|last=Huston|first=Diane|title=Food guide pyramid is built on a base of grains|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2r4cAAAAIBAJ&pg=4658,6907219|accessdate=12 June 2011|newspaper=Daily News|date=29 April 1992|agency=The Associated Press|location=Bowling Green, Kentucky}}</ref>\n\nA modified food pyramid was proposed for adults aged over 70.<ref>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1093/jn/129.3.751|title=Modified Food Guide Pyramid for people over seventy years of age |journal=The Journal of Nutrition |volume=129 |issue=3|pages=751\u2013753 |year=1999 |last1=Russell |first1=Robert M.|last2=Rasmussen |first2=Helen |last3=Lichtenstein |first3=Alice H. |pmid=10082784 |doi-access=free }}</ref>  This \"Modified Food Pyramid for 70+ Adults\" accounted for changing diets with age by emphasizing water consumption as well as nutrient-dense and high-fiber foods.\n\n== MyPyramid ==\n[[File:MyPyramidFood.svg|thumb|left|[[MyPyramid]], the revised USDA food pyramid.]]\n{{main|MyPyramid}}\nIn 2005, the USDA updated its guide with [[MyPyramid]], which replaced the hierarchical levels of the Food Guide Pyramid with colorful vertical wedges, often displayed without images of foods, creating a more abstract design. Stairs were added up the left side of the pyramid with an image of a climber to represent a push for exercise. The share of the pyramid allotted to grains now only narrowly edged out vegetables and milk, which were of equal proportions. Fruits were next in size, followed by a narrower wedge for protein and a small sliver for oils. An unmarked white tip represented discretionary calories for items such as candy, alcohol, or additional food from any other group.<ref>{{cite web|title=MyPyramid -- Getting Started|url=http://www.choosemyplate.gov/downloads/MyPyramid_Getting_Started.pdf|work=United States Department of Agriculture|accessdate=12 June 2011|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==MyPlate==\n[[File:USDA_MyPlate_green.svg|thumb|The [[MyPlate]] nutrition guide]]\n{{main|MyPlate}}\nMyPlate is the current nutrition guide published by the [[United States Department of Agriculture]],<ref name=MyPlate>{{cite web|title=USDA's MyPlate|url=http://www.choosemyplate.gov/|work=United States Department of Agriculture|accessdate=2 June 2011}}</ref> consisting of a diagram of a plate and glass divided into five [[food group]]s. It replaced the USDA's [[MyPyramid]] diagram on June 2, 2011, ending 19 years of [[food guide pyramid|food pyramid]] iconography.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nutrition Plate Unveiled, Replacing Food Pyramid|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/03/business/03plate.html|accessdate=2 June 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2 June 2011}}</ref> The guide will be displayed on food packaging and used in nutritional education in the United States.\n\n==Dietary Guidelines==\n{{main|Dietary Guidelines for Americans}}\nThe [[Center for Nutrition Policy and Promotion]] in the USDA and the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] jointly released a longer textual document called ''[[Dietary Guidelines for Americans]] 2015 - 2020'', to be updated in 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnpp.usda.gov/dietaryguidelines.htm |title=Dietary Guidelines &#124; Center for Nutrition Policy and Promotion |publisher=Cnpp.usda.gov |date= |accessdate=2016-10-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820230816/http://www.cnpp.usda.gov/DietaryGuidelines.htm |archive-date=2014-08-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The first edition was published in 1980, and since 1985 has been updated every five years by the Dietary Guidelines Advisory Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnpp.usda.gov/Publications/DietaryGuidelines/2010/PolicyDoc/Backgrounder.pdf |title=2010 Dietary Guidelines For Americans |accessdate=July 10, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510094406/http://www.cnpp.usda.gov/Publications/DietaryGuidelines/2010/PolicyDoc/Backgrounder.pdf |archivedate=May 10, 2013 }}</ref>  Like the USDA Food Pyramid, these guidelines have been criticized as being overly influenced by the agriculture industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111216006064/en/Internal-Documents-Reveal-USDA-Dietary-Guidelines-Panel |title=Internal Documents Reveal USDA Dietary Guidelines Panel Dominated by ADA |publisher=Business Wire |date=2011-12-16 |accessdate=2016-10-12}}</ref>\nThese criticisms of the Dietary Guidelines arose due to the omission of high-quality evidence that the Public Health Service decided to exclude. The phrasing of recommendations was extremely important and widely affected everyone who read it. The wording had to be changed constantly as there were protests due to comments such as \u201ccut down on fatty meats\u201d, which led to the U.S Department of Agriculture having to stop the publication of the USDA Food Book. Slight alterations of various dietary guidelines had to be made throughout the 1970s and 1980s in an attempt to calm down the protests emerged. As a compromise, the phrase was changed to \u201cchoose lean meat\u201d but didn't result in a better situation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nestle|first1=Marion|title=USDA's Dietary Guidelines: Heath Goals Meets Politics|url=http://www.foodpolitics.com/wp-content/uploads/DietaryGuidelines_CNI_92.pdf}}</ref> In 2015 the committee factored in environmental sustainability for the first time in its recommendations.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://thehill.com/regulation/237767-vegan-diet-best-for-planet-federal-report-says|title = Vegan diet best for planet|last = Wheeler|first = Lydia|date = 5 April 2015|work = thehill.com|access-date = 6 April 2015}}</ref> The committee's 2015 report found that a healthy diet should comprise higher plant based foods and lower animal based foods. It also found that a plant food based diet was better for the environment than one based on meat and dairy.<ref name=\"Mic-20150407\">{{cite web|url=http://mic.com/articles/114710/government-report-confirms-vegan-lifestyle-really-is-better-for-your-body-and-your-planet|title=Government Report Confirms Vegan Lifestyle Really Is Better for Your Body and Your Planet|last=Kleeman|first= Sophie|date=2015-04-07|work=[[Mic (media company)|Mic]]|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 and again in 2015, Edward Archer and colleagues published a series of research articles in PlosOne and Mayo Clinic Proceedings demonstrating that the dietary data used to develop the US Dietary Guidelines were physiologically implausible (i.e., incompatible with survival) and therefore these data were \"inadmissible\" as scientific evidence and should not be used to inform public policy.\n\nIn 2016, Nina Teicholz authored a critique of the US Dietary Guidelines in the British Medical Journal titled The scientific report guiding the US dietary guidelines: is it scientific? Teicholz suggested that \"the scientific committee advising the US government has not used standard methods for most of its analyses and instead relies heavily on systematic reviews from professional bodies such as the [[American Heart Association]] and the [[American College of Cardiology]], which are heavily supported by food and drug companies.\"\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of nutrition guides]]\n*[[5 A Day]]\n* [[Fruits & Veggies \u2013 More Matters]]\n*[[Nutrition facts label]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Nutrition]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Agriculture]]\n[[Category:Publications of the United States government]]\n", "text_old": "The history of [[USDA]] nutrition guides includes over 100 years of American [[nutrition]] advice.  The guides have been updated over time, to adopt new scientific findings and new public health marketing techniques. The current guidelines are the [[Dietary Guidelines for Americans]] 2015 - 2020. Over time they have described from 4 to 11 [[food groups]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Nestle, Marion|title=Food Politics: How the Food Industry Influences Nutrition and Health|year=2013|origyear=2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-27596-6|pages=36\u201337}}</ref> Various guides have been criticized as not accurately representing scientific information about optimal nutrition, and as being overly influenced by the agricultural industries the USDA promotes.\n\n== Earliest guides ==\nThe USDA's first nutrition guidelines were published in 1894 by Dr. [[Wilbur Olin Atwater]] as a farmers' bulletin.<ref name=USDAHistory>{{cite web|title=Dietary Recommendations and How They Have Changed Over Time|url=https://www.ers.usda.gov/webdocs/publications/42215/5831_aib750b_1_.pdf|work=America's Eating Habits: Changes and Consequences|publisher=United States Department of Agriculture|accessdate=2 June 2011|format=PDF|date=May 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/CAT87201446 |title=Farmers' Bulletin No. 23 - Foods : Nutritive Value and Cost |last=Atwater |first=W.O. |year=1894 |website=Internet Archive |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=United States Department of Agriculture}}</ref> In Atwater's 1904 publication titled ''Principles of Nutrition and Nutritive Value of Food,'' he advocated variety, proportionality and moderation; measuring [[food energy|calories]]; and an efficient, affordable diet that focused on nutrient-rich foods and less fat, sugar and [[starch]].<ref>{{cite web|title=USDA Food Pyramid History|url=http://www.healthy-eating-politics.com/usda-food-pyramid.html|work=Healthy Eating Politics|accessdate=2 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228122702/http://www.healthy-eating-politics.com/usda-food-pyramid.html|archive-date=28 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Principles of Nutrition and Nutritive Value of Food|url=https://archive.org/stream/principlesofnutr00atwa|work=Internet Archive|accessdate=2 June 2011}}</ref> This information preceded the discovery of individual [[vitamin]]s beginning in 1910.\n\nA new guide in 1916, ''Food for Young Children'' by nutritionist Caroline Hunt, categorized foods into milk and meat; cereals; vegetables and fruits; fats and fatty foods; and sugars and sugary foods. ''How to Select Food'' in 1917 promoted these five food groups to adults, and the guidelines remained in place through the 1920s. In 1933, the USDA introduced food plans at four different cost levels in response to the [[Great Depression]].<ref name=USDAHistory/>\n\nIn 1941, the first [[Dietary Reference Intake|Recommended Dietary Allowances]] were created, listing specific intakes for [[food energy|calories]], [[protein (nutrient)|protein]], [[iron deficiency (medicine)|iron]], [[calcium#Nutrition|calcium]], and vitamins [[vitamin A|A]], [[thiamine|B<sub>1</sub>]], [[riboflavin|B<sub>2</sub>]] [[niacin|B<sub>3</sub>]], [[vitamin C|C]] and [[vitamin D|D]].<ref name=USDAHistory/>\n\n== Basic 7 ==\n[[File:USDA_-_Basic_7_Food_Groups.jpg|thumb|The USDA's \"Basic 7\" food groups from 1943 to 1956.]]\nIn 1943, during [[World War II]], The USDA introduced a [[nutrition guide]] promoting the \"Basic 7\" [[food group]]s to help maintain nutritional standards under wartime [[Rationing#United States|food rationing]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Food Demonstrations To Be Held Over Nation|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=b9U-AAAAIBAJ&pg=6605,3660154|accessdate=2 June 2011|newspaper=The Tuscaloosa News|date=2 April 1943|agency=The Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=To Demonstrate \"Basic 7\" Diet|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qXNhAAAAIBAJ&pg=4981,1684677|accessdate=2 June 2011|newspaper=The Free Lance-Star|date=2 April 1943|agency=The Associated Press|location=Fredericksburg, Virginia}}</ref> The Basic 7 food groups were:\n\n# Green and yellow vegetables (some raw; some cooked, frozen or canned)\n# Oranges, tomatoes, [[grapefruit]] (or raw [[cabbage]] or [[leaf vegetable|salad greens]])\n# Potatoes and other vegetables and fruits (raw, dried, cooked, frozen or canned)\n# Milk and milk products (fluid, [[evaporated milk|evaporated]], [[powdered milk|dried milk]], or cheese)\n# Meat, poultry, [[fish (food)|fish]], or [[egg (food)|eggs]] (or dried [[bean]]s, [[pea]]s, [[nut (fruit)|nuts]], or [[peanut butter]])\n# Bread, flour, and cereals (natural [[whole grain]], or [[enriched flour|enriched]] or restored)\n# Butter and [[food fortification|fortified]] [[margarine]] (with added Vitamin A)\n\n== Basic Four ==\nFrom 1956 until 1992 the United States Department of Agriculture recommended its \"Basic Four\" food groups.<ref name=Basic4>{{cite web|title=The thing the professor forgot|url=http://naldr.nal.usda.gov/Exe/ZyNET.exe/hgb2290001.xml?ZyActionD=ZyDocument&Client=National%20Agricultural%20Library%20Digital%20Repository&Index=HGB&Docs=&Query=fname%3D%22HGB2290001.XML%22&Time=&EndTime=&SearchMethod=&TocRestrict=&Toc=&TocEntry=&QField=&QFieldYear=&QFieldMonth=&QFieldDay=&UseQField=&IntQFieldOp=0&ExtQFieldOp=0&XmlQuery=&Doc=%3Cdocument%20name%3D%22hgb2290001.xml%22%20path%3D%22%5C%5CNALDR%5CDIGITAL2%5CZYFILES%5CINDEXDATA%5CHGB%5CXML%5C2009%5C00000002%5C%22%20index%3D%22HGB%22%2F%3E&File=%5C%5CNALDR%5CDIGITAL2%5CZYFILES%5CINDEXDATA%5CHGB%5CXML%5C2009%5C00000002%5Chgb2290001.xml&User=ANONYMOUS&Password=anonymous&SortMethod=&MaximumDocuments=0&FuzzyDegree=-1&ImageQuality=r85g16_r85g16_x150y150g16_i500&Display=&DefSeekPage=&SearchBack=ZyActionE&Back=ZyActionS&BackDesc=Results%20page&MaximumPages=-1&ZyEntry=20&SeekPage=f|work=National Agriculture Library Digital Repository|publisher=United States Department of Agriculture|accessdate=3 June 2011}}</ref>{{dead link|date=January 2020}} These food groups were:\n\n* Vegetables and fruits: Recommended as excellent sources of vitamins C and A, and a good source of [[fiber]]. Four or more servings from this group were recommended daily. Previous USDA food guides showed vegetables and fruits as unique groups, each with at least two recommended servings per day.\n* Milk: Recommended as a good source of calcium, [[phosphorus]], protein, riboflavin, and sometimes vitamins A and D. Cheese, [[ice cream]], and [[ice milk]] could sometimes replace milk. Four servings from this group for teens and two for adults were recommended as a minimum daily.\n* Meat: Two daily servings at least were recommended for protein, iron and certain [[B vitamins]]. Includes meat, poultry, fish, eggs, dry beans, dry peas, and peanut butter.\n* Cereals and breads: Whole grain and enriched breads were especially recommended as good sources of iron, B vitamins and [[carbohydrate]]s, as well as sources of protein and fiber. Includes cereals, breads, [[cornmeal]], [[macaroni]], [[noodle]]s, rice and [[spaghetti]]. With the Basic Four daily food guide, the recommended minimum daily servings for the grains group doubled from two to four. Previously, in the Basic Seven guide, refined and non-enriched grains were included along with solid fats and sugar in a cluster of foods outside the essential seven.\n\n\"Other foods\" were said to round out meals and satisfy appetites. These included additional servings from the Basic Four, or foods such as butter, margarine, [[salad dressing]] and [[cooking oil]], [[sauce]]s, [[Fruit preserves|jellies]] and [[syrup]]s.<ref name=Basic4/>\n\nThe Basic Four guide was omnipresent in nutrition [[education in the United States]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Haddix|first=Carol|title=Four basic food groups grow up with the times|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=negLAAAAIBAJ&pg=6552,2002584|accessdate=12 June 2011|newspaper=Evening Independent|date=24 July 1985|agency=Chicago Tribune|location=St. Petersburg, Florida}}</ref> A notable example is the 1972 series [[Mulligan Stew (TV series)|Mulligan Stew]], providing nutrition education for schoolchildren in reruns until 1981.\n\n== Food Guide Pyramid ==\n[[File:USDA Food Pyramid.gif|thumb|The USDA's 1992 [[food guide pyramid]].]]\n{{main|Food Guide Pyramid}}\nThe introduction of the USDA's [[food guide pyramid]] in 1992 attempted to express the recommended servings of each food group, which previous guides did not do. 6 to 11 servings of bread, cereal, rice and pasta occupied the large base of the pyramid; followed by 3 to 5 servings of vegetables; then fruits (2 to 4); then milk, yogurt and cheese (2 to 3); followed by meat, poultry, fish, dry beans, eggs, and nuts (2 to 3); and finally fats, oils and sweets in the small apex (to be used sparingly). Inside each group were several images of representative foods, as well as symbols representing the fat and sugar contents of the foods.<ref>{{cite news|last=Huston|first=Diane|title=Food guide pyramid is built on a base of grains|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2r4cAAAAIBAJ&pg=4658,6907219|accessdate=12 June 2011|newspaper=Daily News|date=29 April 1992|agency=The Associated Press|location=Bowling Green, Kentucky}}</ref>\n\nA modified food pyramid was proposed for adults aged over 70.<ref>{{cite journal |doi= 10.1093/jn/129.3.751|title=Modified Food Guide Pyramid for people over seventy years of age |journal=The Journal of Nutrition |volume=129 |issue=3|pages=751\u2013753 |year=1999 |last1=Russell |first1=Robert M.|last2=Rasmussen |first2=Helen |last3=Lichtenstein |first3=Alice H. |pmid=10082784 |doi-access=free }}</ref>  This \"Modified Food Pyramid for 70+ Adults\" accounted for changing diets with age by emphasizing water consumption as well as nutrient-dense and high-fiber foods.\n\n== MyPyramid ==\n[[File:MyPyramidFood.svg|thumb|left|[[MyPyramid]], the revised USDA food pyramid.]]\n{{main|MyPyramid}}\nIn 2005, the USDA updated its guide with [[MyPyramid]], which replaced the hierarchical levels of the Food Guide Pyramid with colorful vertical wedges, often displayed without images of foods, creating a more abstract design. Stairs were added up the left side of the pyramid with an image of a climber to represent a push for exercise. The share of the pyramid allotted to grains now only narrowly edged out vegetables and milk, which were of equal proportions. Fruits were next in size, followed by a narrower wedge for protein and a small sliver for oils. An unmarked white tip represented discretionary calories for items such as candy, alcohol, or additional food from any other group.<ref>{{cite web|title=MyPyramid -- Getting Started|url=http://www.choosemyplate.gov/downloads/MyPyramid_Getting_Started.pdf|work=United States Department of Agriculture|accessdate=12 June 2011|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==MyPlate==\n[[File:USDA_MyPlate_green.svg|thumb|The [[MyPlate]] nutrition guide]]\n{{main|MyPlate}}\nMyPlate is the current nutrition guide published by the [[United States Department of Agriculture]],<ref name=MyPlate>{{cite web|title=USDA's MyPlate|url=http://www.choosemyplate.gov/|work=United States Department of Agriculture|accessdate=2 June 2011}}</ref> consisting of a diagram of a plate and glass divided into five [[food group]]s. It replaced the USDA's [[MyPyramid]] diagram on June 2, 2011, ending 19 years of [[food guide pyramid|food pyramid]] iconography.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nutrition Plate Unveiled, Replacing Food Pyramid|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/03/business/03plate.html|accessdate=2 June 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2 June 2011}}</ref> The guide will be displayed on food packaging and used in nutritional education in the United States.\n\n==Dietary Guidelines==\n{{main|Dietary Guidelines for Americans}}\nThe [[Center for Nutrition Policy and Promotion]] in the USDA and the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] jointly released a longer textual document called ''[[Dietary Guidelines for Americans]] 2015 - 2020'', to be updated in 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnpp.usda.gov/dietaryguidelines.htm |title=Dietary Guidelines &#124; Center for Nutrition Policy and Promotion |publisher=Cnpp.usda.gov |date= |accessdate=2016-10-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820230816/http://www.cnpp.usda.gov/DietaryGuidelines.htm |archive-date=2014-08-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The first edition was published in 1980, and since 1985 has been updated every five years by the Dietary Guidelines Advisory Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnpp.usda.gov/Publications/DietaryGuidelines/2010/PolicyDoc/Backgrounder.pdf |title=2010 Dietary Guidelines For Americans |accessdate=July 10, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510094406/http://www.cnpp.usda.gov/Publications/DietaryGuidelines/2010/PolicyDoc/Backgrounder.pdf |archivedate=May 10, 2013 }}</ref>  Like the USDA Food Pyramid, these guidelines have been criticized as being overly influenced by the agriculture industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20111216006064/en/Internal-Documents-Reveal-USDA-Dietary-Guidelines-Panel |title=Internal Documents Reveal USDA Dietary Guidelines Panel Dominated by ADA |publisher=Business Wire |date=2011-12-16 |accessdate=2016-10-12}}</ref>\nThese criticisms of the Dietary Guidelines arose due to the omission of high-quality evidence that the Public Health Service decided to exclude. The phrasing of recommendations was extremely important and widely affected everyone who read it. The wording had to be changed constantly as there were protests due to comments such as \u201ccut down on fatty meats\u201d, which led to the U.S Department of Agriculture having to stop the publication of the USDA Food Book. Slight alterations of various dietary guidelines had to be made throughout the 1970s and 1980s in an attempt to calm down the protests emerged. As a compromise, the phrase was changed to \u201cchoose lean meat\u201d but didn't result in a better situation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nestle|first1=Marion|title=USDA's Dietary Guidelines: Heath Goals Meets Politics|url=http://www.foodpolitics.com/wp-content/uploads/DietaryGuidelines_CNI_92.pdf}}</ref> In 2015 the committee factored in environmental sustainability for the first time in its recommendations.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://thehill.com/regulation/237767-vegan-diet-best-for-planet-federal-report-says|title = Vegan diet best for planet|last = Wheeler|first = Lydia|date = 5 April 2015|work = thehill.com|access-date = 6 April 2015}}</ref> The committee's 2015 report found that a healthy diet should comprise higher plant based foods and lower animal based foods. It also found that a plant food based diet was better for the environment than one based on meat and dairy.<ref name=\"Mic-20150407\">{{cite web|url=http://mic.com/articles/114710/government-report-confirms-vegan-lifestyle-really-is-better-for-your-body-and-your-planet|title=Government Report Confirms Vegan Lifestyle Really Is Better for Your Body and Your Planet|last=Kleeman|first= Sophie|date=2015-04-07|work=[[Mic (media company)|Mic]]|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 and again in 2015, Edward Archer and colleagues published a series of research articles in PlosOne and Mayo Clinic Proceedings demonstrating that the dietary data used to develop the US Dietary Guidelines were physiologically implausible (i.e., incompatible with survival) and therefore these data were \"inadmissible\" as scientific evidence and should not be used to inform public policy.\n\nIn 2016, Nina Teicholz authored a critique of the US Dietary Guidelines in the British Medical Journal titled The scientific report guiding the US dietary guidelines: is it scientific? Teicholz suggested that \"the scientific committee advising the US government has not used standard methods for most of its analyses and instead relies heavily on systematic reviews from professional bodies such as the [[American Heart Association]] and the [[American College of Cardiology]], which are heavily supported by food and drug companies.\"\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of nutrition guides]]\n*[[5 A Day]]\n* [[Fruits & Veggies \u2013 More Matters]]\n*[[Nutrition facts label]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Nutrition]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Agriculture]]\n[[Category:Publications of the United States government]]\n", "name_user": "Lifestox", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Dead link has been revoked by useful link)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_USDA_nutrition_guides"}
{"title_page": "Lady on the Rock (statue)", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Lady on the Rock statues in Dublin (2015).jpg|thumb|Lady on the Rock statues in Dublin (2015)]]\n\nThe '''Lady On The Rock''', also known as the '''White Lady''', is a popular plaster [[Figurine|statue]] that is seen in the windows of many residential homes in [[Dublin]] city. Its popularity has led to many theories about the meaning and significance of the statue.<ref name=McDonald>{{cite web|last1=McDonald|first1=Karl|title=Lady On The Rock: Tracing The Phenomenon of Dublin\u2019s Own Venus De Milo|url=http://totallydublin.ie/more/lady-on-the-rock-tracing-the-phenomenon-of-dublins-own-venus-de-milo/|website=Totally Dublin|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nThe statue features a reclining woman draped in fabric. Originally made as a clay model by artist Harold Gardiner around 1993, it was then cast in fibreglass by Edward Loughman of RPM Supplies. Gardiner had the mould made so as to gift the statue to friends and family. When Gardiner died in 1995 Loughman cleared out Gardiner's workshop at his widow's request and took the cast of the Lady. Loughman subsequently sold the cast to Vincent Doran of Dublin Mouldings. Since then the statue has been produced and sold by Dublin Mouldings, a shop and workshop on [[Parnell Street]].<ref name=McDonald /><ref name=\"Kelly\">{{cite web|last1=Kelly|first1=John|title=The Alluring Statuette Dividing Dublin|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/lady-on-the-rock-dublin-statue|website=Atlas Obscura|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Theories of the meaning==\nThe popularity of the statue has led to many theories emerging about the significance of the Lady. She is most prevalent on the north side of the city, and in areas such as the [[Liberties, Dublin|Liberties]]. A residence will often have numerous statues, one in each window.<ref name=Loftus>{{cite web|last1=Loftus|first1=Valerie|title=7 little things in Dublin you\u2019ve always wondered about|url=http://www.dailyedge.ie/dublin-details-youve-always-wondered-about-1614722-Aug2014/|website=The Daily Edge|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> Some have suggested that the presence of the statue in a window marks a brothel, that drugs are available for sale, or that protection money has been paid by the resident. Others have suggested that she represents [[Molly Malone]].<ref name=McDonald /> There is also speculation that she could represent the [[Virgin Mary]] or [[Mary Magdalene]].<ref name=\"Kelly\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Californian artist, Jessie Ward, won the 2010 [[Darklight Film Festival|Darklight Festival]]'s Free Your Film contest for her short film about the Lady.<ref name=McDonald /> The White Lady art gallery is named after her, and sells versions of the lady painted in different ways.<ref>{{cite web|title=White Lady art gallery|url=https://www.dublinfunguide.ie/places/white-lady-art|website=Dublin Fun Guide|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> In 2015, a group of secondary school students investigated and created their own versions of the white lady, which were subsequently exhibited in the axis:Ballymun.<ref name=Barry>{{cite web|last1=Barry|first1=Aoife|title=What\u2019s the real story behind this famous statue?|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/lady-of-the-rock-dublin-history-1960458-Feb2015/|website=The Journal|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> The statue has also been made into a Christmas decoration.<ref name=McLysaght>{{cite web|last1=McLysaght|first1=Emer|title=There\u2019s now a \u2018White Lady of the Northside\u2019 Christmas decoration|url=http://www.dailyedge.ie/our-lady-of-the-northside-white-lady-christmas-1187309-Nov2013/|website=The Daily Edge|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uyIZiB-T1Sk ''Lady On The Rock'' by Jessie Ward (Youtube)]\n\n[[Category:Sculptures in Ireland]]\n[[Category:1993 sculptures]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Lady on the Rock statues in Dublin (2015).jpg|thumb|Lady on the Rock statues in Dublin (2015)]]\n\nThe '''Lady On The Rock''', also known as the '''White Lady''', is a popular plaster [[Figurine|statue]] that is seen in the windows of many residential homes in [[Dublin]] city. Its popularity has led to many theories about the meaning and significance of the statue.<ref name=McDonald>{{cite web|last1=McDonald|first1=Karl|title=Lady On The Rock: Tracing The Phenomenon of Dublin\u2019s Own Venus De Milo|url=http://totallydublin.ie/more/lady-on-the-rock-tracing-the-phenomenon-of-dublins-own-venus-de-milo/|website=Totally Dublin|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nThe statue features a reclining woman draped in fabric. Originally made as a clay model by artist Harold Gardiner around 1993, it was then cast in fibreglass by Edward Loughman of RPM Supplies. Gardiner had the mould made so as to gift the statue to friends and family. When Gardiner died in 1995 Loughman cleared out Gardiner's workshop at his widow's request and took the cast of the Lady. Loughman subsequently sold the cast to Vincent Doran of Dublin Mouldings. Since then the statue has been produced and sold by Dublin Mouldings, a shop and workshop on [[Parnell Street]].<ref name=McDonald /><ref name=\"Kelly\">{{cite web|last1=Kelly|first1=John|title=The Alluring Statuette Dividing Dublin|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/lady-on-the-rock-dublin-statue|website=Atlas Obscura|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Theories of the meaning==\nThe popularity of the statue has led to many theories emerging about the significance of the Lady. She is most prevalent on the north side of the city, and in areas such as the [[Liberties, Dublin|Liberties]]. A residence will often have numerous statues, one in each window.<ref name=Loftus>{{cite web|last1=Loftus|first1=Valerie|title=7 little things in Dublin you\u2019ve always wondered about|url=http://www.dailyedge.ie/dublin-details-youve-always-wondered-about-1614722-Aug2014/|website=The Daily Edge|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> Some have suggested that the presence of the statue in a window marks a brothel, that drugs are available for sale, or that protection money has been paid by the resident. Others have suggested that she represents [[Molly Malone]].<ref name=McDonald /> There is also speculation that she could represent the [[Virgin Mary]] or [[Mary Magdalene]].<ref name=\"Kelly\" />\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Californian artist, Jessie Ward, won the 2010 Darklight Festival's Free Your Film contest for her short film about the Lady.<ref name=McDonald /> The White Lady art gallery is named after her, and sells versions of the lady painted in different ways.<ref>{{cite web|title=White Lady art gallery|url=https://www.dublinfunguide.ie/places/white-lady-art|website=Dublin Fun Guide|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref> In 2015, a group of secondary school students investigated and created their own versions of the white lady, which were subsequently exhibited in the axis:Ballymun.<ref name=Barry>{{cite web|last1=Barry|first1=Aoife|title=What\u2019s the real story behind this famous statue?|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/lady-of-the-rock-dublin-history-1960458-Feb2015/|website=The Journal|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> The statue has also been made into a Christmas decoration.<ref name=McLysaght>{{cite web|last1=McLysaght|first1=Emer|title=There\u2019s now a \u2018White Lady of the Northside\u2019 Christmas decoration|url=http://www.dailyedge.ie/our-lady-of-the-northside-white-lady-christmas-1187309-Nov2013/|website=The Daily Edge|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uyIZiB-T1Sk ''Lady On The Rock'' by Jessie Ward (Youtube)]\n\n[[Category:Sculptures in Ireland]]\n[[Category:1993 sculptures]]\n", "name_user": "M.nelson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn popular culture:wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lady_on_the_Rock_(statue)"}
{"title_page": "Wuhan Metro", "text_new": "{{Infobox Public transit\n| name = Wuhan Metro\n| image = Wuhan Metro Logo.svg\n| imagesize = 75px\n| image2 = Rolling stock NO. A62 of Wuhan Metro Line 1.jpg\n| imagesize2 = 300px\n| caption2=The train of Line 1 departing from [[Zongguan Station]]\n| locale = [[Wuhan]]\n| transit_type = [[Rapid transit]]\n| began_operation = {{Start date and age|2004|07|28|df=yes}}\n| system_length = {{convert|339|km|mi|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=Wuhan8-3 />\n| lines = 9\n| train_length = 4 or 6 cars\n| vehicles = \n| stations = 228<ref name=Wuhan8-3 />\n| ridership = *3.642 million (April 2019)<ref name=\u5168\u6765\u4e86\uff012019\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u8fd0\u91cf\u603b\u7ed3>{{Cite web |url = https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/7aCHDocl1-JvLA9QEJPQsw |script-title=zh:\u5168\u6765\u4e86\uff012019\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u8fd0\u91cf\u603b\u7ed3 |author =[[WeChat]]@\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u6d41\u53ca\u8fd0\u8f93\u7814\u7a76\u963f\u725b |date = 2020-02-15 |publisher = \u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a }}</ref> \n*4.465 million (Maximum, 4 April 2019)<ref name=\"peak ridership\">{{cite web |url=https://m.sohu.com/a/306708478_664673/?pvid=000115_3w_a&sec=wd|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u6e05\u660e\u5c0f\u957f\u5047\u9001\u5ba21615\u4e07\u4e58\u6b21\uff0c\u5ba2\u6d41\u91cf42\u5929\u5185\u4e09\u521b\u7eaa\u5f55}}</ref>\n| annual_ridership = 1.22 billion (2019)<ref name=\u5168\u6765\u4e86\uff012019\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u8fd0\u91cf\u603b\u7ed3></ref>\n| track_gauge = {{Track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| reporting marks = \n| operator = Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd.\n| owner = Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd.\n| website = {{url|www.wuhanrt.com|www.wuhanrt.com}}\n| map = [[File:Route Map of Wuhan Metro.svg|300px]]\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| area served = \n| line_number = \n| start = \n| headway =2.5 - 9 min\n| end = \n| chief_executive = \n| character = Elevated and underground\n| map_state = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s2=\u6b66\u6c49\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\n|t2=\u6b66\u6f22\u8ecc\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\n|p2=W\u01d4h\u00e0n Gu\u01d0d\u00e0o Ji\u0101ot\u014dng\n|s=\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\n|t=\u6b66\u6f22\u5730\u9435\n|p=W\u01d4h\u00e0n D\u00ecti\u011b\n|order=st\n}}\nThe '''Wuhan Metro''' is a [[rapid transit]] system serving the city of [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China, owned and operated by Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd. \nThe system began operation on July 28, 2004 with the completion of a ten-station long elevated line between [[Huangpu Road Station|Huangpu Road]] and [[Zongguan Station|Zongguan]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ctdsb.cnhubei.com/html/ctdsb/20110409/ctdsb1348512.html |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f7b\u8f68\u4eca\u8fce\u7b2c1\u4ebf\u540d\u4e58\u5ba2 |script-work=zh:\u8346\u695a\u7f51-\u695a\u5929\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5 |language=Chinese |date=April 9, 2011}}</ref> making Wuhan the sixth city in [[mainland China]] to have a metro system after [[Beijing Subway|Beijing]], [[Tianjin Metro|Tianjin]], [[Shanghai Metro|Shanghai]], [[Guangzhou Metro|Guangzhou]] and [[Dalian Metro|Dalian]].<ref>[http://urbanrail.net/as/wuha/wuhan.htm Wuhan], ''UrbanRail.net''</ref> Line 1 is the first metro line in China to have been wrongly referred to as a light rail ({{zh|labels=no |s=\u8f7b\u8f68 |p=q\u012bng gu\u01d0}}) system in Chinese terminology.<ref>Wuhan, along with other three Chinese cities, has been the first batch to be approved to build so-called \"light rail\" system in China since 2000, see {{cite web |url=http://news.huochepiao.com/2012-7/20127177020183.htm |script-title=zh:2000\u5e74\uff0c\u56fd\u5bb6\u6279\u51c6\u957f\u6625\u3001\u5927\u8fde\u3001\u6b66\u6c49\u548c\u91cd\u5e864\u4e2a\u57ce\u5e02\u4e3a\u9996\u6279\u8f7b\u8f68\u5efa\u8bbe\u793a\u8303\u57ce\u5e02}}. However, [[Changchun]] built a true light-rail system, [[Dalian]] built a metro-style commuter rail system (and is referred to as {{zh|s=\u5feb\u8f68 |p=ku\u00e0i gu\u01d0}}, not {{zh|links=no |s=\u8f7b\u8f68 |p=q\u012bng gu\u01d0}}), and [[Chongqing]] opted for a monorail system, whereas Wuhan was the only one to build an elevated metro system. See [http://urbanrail.net/as/wuha/wuhan.htm \"Urbanrail--Wuhan\"] and affiliated Wikipedia pages. See also a comment from He Jibin, an Urban Planning official from Wuhan Municipality: \"{{lang|zh-Hans|\u4e0d\u8981\u8ba4\u4e3a\u5730\u4e0b\u7684\u624d\u662f\u5730\u94c1\uff0c1\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e5f\u662f\u5730\u94c1\u7684\u4e00\u79cd\u65b9\u5f0f...\u4f55\u7ee7\u658c\u5f00\u95e8\u89c1\u5c71\u5730\u7ea0\u6b63\u6982\u5ff5\uff0c\u4ed6\u662f\u6b66\u6c49\u5e02\u56fd\u571f\u89c4\u5212\u5c40\u4ea4\u901a\u5e02\u653f\u5904\u5904\u957f\u2026\u2026}}\" {{cite journal | url=http://dawuhan.cnhubei.com/ |script-title=zh:\u90a3\u4e9b\u5e74\uff0c\u6211\u4eec\u4e00\u8d77\u8ffd\u7684\u5730\u94c1 | author=Li Fei (\u674e\u6590) |script-journal=zh:\u5927\u6b66\u6c49 |date=March 2012 | volume=148 | page=33}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019|November}}, there are 9 lines in operation, totaling 228 stations and {{Convert|339|km|mi}} of system length.<ref name=Wuhan8-3 />\n\nWuhan Metro is pursuing ambitious expansion projects to connect Wuhan's three boroughs, divided by the [[Yangtze River]] and [[Han River (Hubei)|Han River]], to accommodate increasing inter-borough traffic and provide commuter services to suburban [[Satellite city|satellite cities]]. Its future expansion includes the operation of 12 urban lines and 13 suburban lines, totaling a length of {{convert|1045|km|mi}}, making it one of the most expansive rail transit systems in the world. As of 2017, there are currently 13 subway expansion projects totaling {{convert|304|km|abbr=on}} of subway being constructed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://m.xinhuanet.com/hb/2018-10/01/c_1123512458.htm |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf11\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a \u957f\u6c5f\u516c\u94c1\u96a7\u9053\u540c\u65f6\u542f\u7528|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Wuhan_Metro_Timelapse2019.gif|thumb|400px|Evolution of the Wuhan Metro]]\n\nPreliminary studies of urban rail transit system were prompted by the city shortly after a [[National Railway Company of Belgium|Belgian Railways]] delegation visit in 1984. Following the demolition of old [[Beijing-Hankou Railway]], the city of [[Wuhan]] planned to utilize the corridor to construct the city's first rapid transit rail line. In September 1992, the [[Wuhan Metro Construction Group]] was established by [[Wuhan Municipal Construction Commission]] and a supervision group, led by the mayor [[Qian Yunlu]], was subsequently formed in 1993 to facilitate the project's funding, planning, logistics, and organization. Yet, it was seven years before the city was able to fund construction.\n\nIn October 1999, the [[National Development and Reform Commission|National Planning Commission]] (predecessor of the National Development and Reform Commission) approved the Wuhan \"Light Rail\" project (Line 1, phase 1), signaling the start of serious work on the rail transit project. On October 2, 2000, the [[Wuhan|Wuhan Municipal Government]] ratified the establishment of the [[Wuhan Rail Transit Co., Ltd]]., and contracted construction, operation, administration and related real estate development to the corporation.\n\nIn December 2000, the National Planning Commission accepted a feasibility report on the project and approved construction on phase 1 of Line 1. On December 23, 2000, the project broke ground and comprehensive construction began.\n\nIn 2002, with the anticipation of an economic boom and increasing demand for urban rail transit, Wuhan Municipal Government approved the city's first long-term rail transit master plan. On July 28, 2004, the ten-station long \"light rail\" line was opened to the public and entered revenue service in August. However, low ridership discouraged the city from funding the extension project, for which ground had been broken on December 15, 2005, and a 4-year delay in construction ensued. In April, 2006, the [[National Development and Reform Commission|NDRC]] ratified a six-year construction/operation plan, but it was not until a year later on April 9, 2007 that NDRC accepted the feasibility report for line 1, phase 2 (the extension project) and approved construction on the project.\n\nIn the interim, construction began on the [[Fanhu station]] of the fully underground line 2 on November 16, 2006, as a response to the six-year plan adopted by NDRC earlier. Construction also began on the underground line 4 stations of [[Wuchang railway station]] in June, and [[Wuhan railway station]] in September, as parts of the integral capital project to revamp and construct the [[Wuhan Railway Hub System|Wuhan Railway Hub]].\n\nIn May 2007, the [[Hubei Provincial Development and Reform Commission]] (HDRC) approved preliminary designs on the Line 1, phase 2, and comprehensive construction subsequently commenced in June. On May 15, the city government approved the establishment of [[Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd]]., which would replace the [[Wuhan Rail Transit Co., Ltd]] and assume its responsibilities and benefits.\n\nOn September 12, 2007, the NDRC accepted the feasibility report to Line 2, phase 1, and preliminary designs were approved by the HDRC in December 2007. However, it was not until September 2008 that land purchases and funding were facilitated and comprehensive construction began to take place. In October 2009, drilling of the [[Yangtze River]] tunnel started.\n\nOn March 13, 2009, the NDRC accepted feasibility report to Line 4, phase 1. On May 13, 2009, the HDRC ratified preliminary designs on Line 4, phase 1. Comprehensive construction ensued on the [[Wuchang District|Wuchang]] segment of Line 4. A more ambitious urban rapid transit plan was submitted for NDRC review in October, 2009, and in late November, on-site panel investigations were conducted by [[China International Engineering Consulting Corporation]].\n\nIn February 2010 (Wuhan Metro)'s first commercial property topped out in [[Hanxi 1st Road station]]. On July 29, Line 1 phase 2 entered revenue service from [[Dijiao station|Dijiao]] to [[Dongwu Boulevard station|Dongwu Boulevard]]. Despite plans to extend the westernmost terminus to [[Jinshan Avenue]] in [[Dongxihu District]], the station was never built. A short stub with crossover tracks was constructed behind Dongwu Boulevard. [[Zhuyehai]], a station in [[Qiaokou District]], remained non-operational in spite of the existence of complete platforms. Neither exits nor staircases had been built yet. It was due to open when the Wuhan [[IKEA]] store was completed in late 2014.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u8f7b\u8f68\u4e8c\u671f\u589e\u8bbe\u7af9\u53f6\u6d77\u7ad9 |url=http://hb.qq.com/a/20090531/000131.htm |language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nA revised and more detailed construction plan was accepted by the NDRC on January 31, 2011. The plan specified the city's plan to complete construction on Line 3, 4, 6, 7 and 8 before 2017. Beginning on March 1, Line 1 subdivided its fare zones from 3 to 5 and lowered maximum fare from 5 CNY / ride to 4 CNY / ride. [[Wuhan Tong]] cardholders will receive a 20 percent discount on single ride fares.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f7b\u8f68\u7968\u4ef7\u4e0b\u8c03 |url=http://www.hb.xinhuanet.com/newscenter/2011-03/03/content_22188105.htm |language=Chinese}}</ref> On April 9, Line 1 welcomed its 100,000,000th customer, who was awarded a one-year pass to the Metro.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f7b\u8f68\u5ba2\u6d41\u91cf\u4eca\u65e5\u7a81\u78341\u4ebf |url=http://news.cnxianzai.com/2011/04/324488.html |language=Chinese}}</ref> On September 9, preliminary designs on Line 4, phase 2 ([[Hanyang District|Hanyang]] segment) was approved by HDRC.\n\nOn February 17, 2012, the NDRC accepted a feasibility report on line 3, phase 1, the fourth line in Wuhan Metro's grid and the first to cross the [[Han River (Yangtze River tributary)|Han River]], connecting the boroughs of [[Hankou]] and [[Hanyang District|Hanyang]]. A feasibility report to Line 6\u2014the second Hankou-Hanyang connection\u2014was also approved by the NDRC on December 21, 2012. Seven days later, line 2 entered revenue service, connecting some of the most populated areas of Hankou, Wuchang, and the [[Optics Valley of China|Optics Valley]].\n\nOn April 12, 2013, the NDRC granted acceptance to a feasibility report of Line 8, phase 1, which connects Hankou and Wuchang via the [[Second Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge|Second Yangtze River Bridge]] corridor. Construction began in June 2013 and was completed in December 2017.\n\n[[File:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf\u8f66\u53a2\u5185\u4fdd\u6301\u793e\u4ea4\u8ddd\u79bb\u7684\u63d0\u793a.jpg|thumb|right|Notices in the carriage of Line 7 to remind people to maintain social distancing during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Hubei]].]]\n\nOn 23 January 2020, the entire metro network was shut down, along with all other public transport in the city, including national railway and air travel, to halt the spread of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Hubei]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/01/22/798602296/public-transport-in-wuhan-suspended-due-to-coronavirus-concerns|title=Public Transport In Wuhan Suspended Due To Coronavirus Concerns|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51215348|title=Virus-hit Chinese city shuts public transport|date=2020-01-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nOn 28 March 2020, six lines (Line 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7) resumed operation, after two-month [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|lockdown]]. Line 8, Line 11, and Yangluo Line remain out of service.<ref name=\"resume\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/25/c_138914547.htm|title=Wuhan buses hit the road after two-month lockdown|website=Xinhua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nOn {{date|2020-4-8}}, Line 8 Phase 1 resumed operation. Line 8 Phase 3, Line 11 and Yangluo Line remain suspended.<ref>{{Cite web |url =http://www.chinanews.com/gn/2020/04-07/9150068.shtml|title =\u6b66\u6c49\uff1a4\u67088\u65e5\u8d77\u6062\u590d\u51fa\u79df\u8f66\u8fd0\u8425 \u9002\u65f6\u6062\u590d\u7f51\u7ea6\u8f66\u8fd0\u8425|author =Huang Lei\uff1bWang Yang|date =2020-04-07 |publisher =Hubei Daily}}</ref>\n\n===Timeline of service expansion===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Segment description\n!Date opened\n!Station(s)\n!# of new stations\n!Length (km)\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 1\n|{{date|2004-7-28}}\n|Zongguan \u2014 Huangpu Road\n|10{{NoteTag|in which Taipingyang Station was postponed to open on {{date|2006-4-8}}.}}\n|9.769\n|-\n|Phase \u2161 of Line 1\n|{{date|2010-7-29}}\n| Dongwu Boulevard \u2014 Zongguan;<br> Huangpu Road \u2014 Dijiao\n|16{{NoteTag|in which Zhuyehai Station was postponed to open on {{date|2014-9-17}}.<ref>[http://qzgh.qiaokou.gov.cn/qkxw/bmdt/201409/t20140917_139172.shtml \u8f7b\u8f68\u7af9\u53f6\u6d77\u7ad9\u5b9c\u5bb6\u8054\u5eca\u6865\u6295\u5165\u4f7f\u7528 (Zhuyehai station opened)]</ref>}}\n|18.494\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 2\n|{{date|2012-12-28}}\n| Jinyintan \u2014 Optics Valley Square\n|21\n|27.152\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 4<ref>[http://cjweek.cjn.cn/html/2013-12/27/content_5269051.htm Section one of Metro Line 4 opens]</ref>\n|{{date|2013-12-28}}\n| Wuchang Railway Station \u2014 Wuhan Railway Station\n|15\n|17.974\n|-\n|Hankou North extension of Line 1\n|{{date|2014-5-28}}\n|  Dijiao \u2014 Hankou North\n|3\n|5.555 \n|-\n|Phase \u2161 of Line 4\n|{{date|2014-12-28}}\n| Huangjinkou \u2014 Wuchang Railway Station\n|13\n|15.429\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 3<ref name=\"Line 3\">{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5373\u5c06\u5730\u94c1\u6210\u73af \"\u73af\u91d1\u65f6\u4ee3\"\u91cd\u6784\u5546\u4e1a\u5730\u7406 