ne 12 </span>]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| ''loop line''\n| 2023\n| 60.4\n| 35\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|19}}\" | [[Line 19, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 19 </span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| {{WHM stations|Optics Valley Free Trade Zone}}\n| 2023\n| 24.45\n| 9\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|7}}\" | [[Line 7, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Northern extension of Line 7</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Machi}}\n| {{WHM stations|Huangpi Square}}\n| 2024\n| 36\n| 10\n| bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"| Under construction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|10}}\" |  [[Line 10, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Xingang Line</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| {{WHM stations|Shigang}}\n| 2025\n| 26.2\n| 10\n| bgcolor=\"lightblue\"| Approved\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|10}}\" |  [[Line 10, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 10</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Changfu}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| 2025\n| 61.4\n| 29\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|21}}\" |  [[Yangluo line|<span STYLE=\" color:white\"> Phase 2 of Yangluo Line</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zhongyi Road}}\n| {{WHM stations|Houhu Boulevard}}\n| TBD\n| 3.2\n| 2\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|13}}\" |  [[Line 13, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 13</span>]]\n| [[New Hanyang railway station|New Hanyang Railway Station]]\n| {{WHM stations|Future Tech-city}}\n| TBD\n| 40.4\n| 27\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|14}}\" |  [[Line 14, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 14</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Zhuyehai}}\n| {{WHM stations|Dijiao}}\n| TBD\n| 27.2\n| 21\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#{{WHM color|20}}\" |  [[Line 20, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 20</span>]]\n| {{WHM stations|Tianhe International Airport}}\n| {{WHM stations|Wuhan}}\n| TBD\n| 30.3\n| 6\n| bgcolor=\"lightpink\"| Under Planning\n|}\n\n==Station==\nAlmost all stations, except the stations on Line 1, are equipped with [[platform screen door]]s. There is a plan that stations on Line 1 will be equipped with [[platform screen door]]s in the future.<ref>{{Cite web |url = http://news.cjn.cn/sywh/201505/t2642859.htm |title = \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c11\u53f7\u7ebf\u5c06\u5168\u7ebf\u5b89\u88c5\u7ad9\u53f0\u5b89\u5168\u95e8 \u4e0e\u5faa\u793c\u95e8\u7ad9\u4e00\u81f4 |author =\u9676\u5e38\u5b81\uff1b\u80e1\u7434|date = 2015-05-04 |publisher = \u6b66\u6c49\u6668\u62a5 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url =http://hb.sina.cn/news/2016-01-16/detail-ifxnqrkc6501288.d.html?from=wap#_cnbk_ |title = \u6b66\u6c49\u5973\u4e58\u5ba2\u610f\u5916\u8dcc\u4e0b1\u53f7\u7ebf\u7ad9\u53f0 \u8f7b\u8f68\u5b89\u5168\u95e8\u8fdf\u8fdf\u4e0d\u88c5 |author =\u5218\u5b5d\u658c\uff1b\u9ec4\u58eb\u5cf0 |date = 2016-01-06 |publisher=\u695a\u5929\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5}}</ref> The metro stations are equipped to be disabled and elderly friendly, with automatic fare collection system, announcement system, electronic display boards, escalators and lifts. The stations are equipped with non-slippery flooring with grip-rails, audio announcements and Braille facilities to help visually challenged passengers. \n\n===Gallery===\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|footer=\n|lines=2\n|width=200\n|height=150\n|align=center\n|File:Zhuyeshan Station 03.jpg|Station entrance\n|File:Guidepost of Wuhan Metro.jpg|Guidepost\n|File:\u4e2d\u5c71\u516c\u56ed.jpg|Zhongshan Park Station\n|File:Wuhan Business District Station 09.jpg|The hall of Wuhan Business District Station\n|File:Huangpu Road Station in 2017 (6).jpg|The hall of Huangpu Road Station, Line 8\n|File:Widened Platform of Wuhan Metro Line 1 Huangpu Road Station.jpg|Widened Platform of Huangpu Road Station, Line 1\n|File:Wuhan Metro Line 7 Pangxiejia Station Platform (2).jpg|Pangxiejia Station Platform, Line 7\n|File:Wangjiawan Station 02.jpg|The hall of Wangjiawan Station\n|File:Tianhe International Airport Station (Metro) 02.jpg|Tianhe International Airport Station\n|File:Xujiapeng Station (3).jpg|Xujiapeng Station platform, Line 8\n|File:Sanyang Rd. Station, Wuhan Metro Line 7 (2).jpg|Transfer passage at Sanyang Road Station\n|File:Hall of Matoutan Park Station.jpg|The hall of Matoutan Park Station\n|File:Hall of Luoxiong Road Station.jpg|The hall of Luoxiong Road Station\n|File:Hall of Hanzheng Street Station (1).jpg|The hall of Hanzheng Street Station\n|File:Platform of Hanzheng Street Station.jpg|The platform of Hanzheng Street Station\n|File:English zhongnan & hongguang.svg|Cross-platform transfer \n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Trams in Wuhan]]\n*[[Wuhan Metro Museum]]\n*[[List of rapid transit systems]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Wuhan Metro}}\n*[http://www.wuhanrt.com/ Official site] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[http://www.urbanrail.net/as/cn/wuhan/wuhan.htm UrbanRail.net's page on the Wuhan Metro]\n\n{{Hubei transit}}\n{{Rapid transit in the People's Republic of China}}\n\n[[Category:Wuhan Metro| ]]\n[[Category:Rapid transit in China]]\n[[Category:Underground rapid transit in China]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Projects established in 1979]]\n", "name_user": "Painjet", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTicketing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wuhan_Metro"}
{"title_page": "Whitehope Heights", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = \n| photo = Whitehope Heights - geograph.org.uk - 1178681.jpg\n| photo_caption = \n| elevation_m = 637\n| elevation_ref = <ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1895</ref>\n|title= \n| prominence_m = 109\n| prominence_ref = <ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1895</ref>\n| listing = [[List of Donald mountains in Scotland|Donald]]\n| translation =\n| language =\n| pronunciation =\n| location = [[Dumfries and Galloway]], [[Scottish Borders]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = [[Moffat Hills]], [[Southern Uplands]]\n| coordinates = \n| grid_ref_UK = NT 09575 13898\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 78\n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\n'''Whitehope Heights''' is a hill in the [[Moffat Hills]] range, part of the [[Southern Uplands]] of [[Scotland]]. The lowest [[Donald (hill)|Donald]] hill in the range, it is separated from [[Hart Fell]] by a steep grassy cleuch known as The Gyle. Like its neighbour, the [[Dumfries and Galloway]]-[[Scottish Borders]] border runs along its summit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mountainsofscotland.co.uk/Maps/mapdonalds.htm|title=New Donalds Map|website=www.mountainsofscotland.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The southern slopes of the hill are part of the Corehead hill farm, an area owned by the [[Borders Forest Trust]] for the purposes of habitat regeneration; as a result, a large deer fence lines the boundary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bordersforesttrust.org/places/wild-heart/corehead-devils-beef-tub/|title=Corehead & Devil's Beef Tub - Borders Forest Trust|website=bordersforesttrust.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> East of the [[Devil's Beef Tub]] and [[Annandale Way]], it is most frequently climbed from this direction, but ascents from Hart Fell are also common.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1895|title=Whitehope Heights|website=www.hill-bagging.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = \n| photo = Whitehope Heights - geograph.org.uk - 1178681.jpg\n| photo_caption = \n| elevation_m = 637\n| elevation_ref = <ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1895</ref>\n|title= \n| prominence_m = 109\n| prominence_ref = <ref>http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1895</ref>\n| listing = [[List of Donald mountains in Scotland|Donald]]\n| translation =\n| language =\n| pronunciation =\n| location = [[Dumfries and Galloway]], [[Scottish Borders]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = [[Moffat Hills]], [[Southern Uplands]]\n| coordinates = \n| grid_ref_UK = NT 09575 13898\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 78\n| easiest_route = \n}}\n\n'''Whitehope Heights''' is a hill in the [[Moffat Hills]] range, part of the [[Southern Uplands]] of [[Scotland]]. The lowest [[Donald (hill)|Donald]] hill in the range, it is separated from [[Hart Fell]] by a steep grassy cleuch known as The Gyle. Like its neighbour, the [[Dumfries and Galloway]]-[[Scottish Borders]] border runs along its summit. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mountainsofscotland.co.uk/Maps/mapdonalds.htm|title=New Donalds Map|website=www.mountainsofscotland.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The southern slopes of the hill are part of the Corehead hill farm, an area owned by the [[Borders Forest Trust]] for the purposes of habitat regeneration; as a result, a large deer fence lines the boundary. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bordersforesttrust.org/places/wild-heart/corehead-devils-beef-tub/|title=Corehead & Devil's Beef Tub - Borders Forest Trust|website=bordersforesttrust.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> East of the [[Devil's Beef Tub]] and [[Annandale Way]], it is most frequently climbed from this direction, but ascents from Hart Fell are also common.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hill-bagging.co.uk/mountaindetails.php?qu=S&rf=1895|title=Whitehope Heights|website=www.hill-bagging.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addeduncategorisedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitehope_Heights"}
{"title_page": "Rafael Gumucio", "text_new": "[[File:Gumucio, Rafael -05.JPG|thumb|Gumucio in April 2015]]\n'''Rafael Gumucio Araya''' (born January 15, 1970 in [[Santiago de Chile|Santiago]]) is a [[Chilean people|Chilean]] writer and comedian.\n\n== Biography ==\n\nHe is son of the historian Rafael Luis Gumucio Rivas, grandson of the left-wing politician Rafael Agust\u00edn Gumucio, and the cousin of filmmaker and also politician [[Marco Enr\u00edquez-Ominami]]. He attended high school at the Colegio Regina Pacis in [[\u00d1u\u00f1oa]];,<ref>[http://diario.elmercurio.com/detalle/index.asp?id={8f628aa8-5b8e-486d-bf4a-ca23871d1d21} \u00d3scar Contardo. ''Las quejas del conde disl\u00e9xico''], ''[[El Mercurio]]'', 23.06.2002; last accessed on 30.03.2012</ref> graduated as a Spanish language teacher first and then as a Master in Literature at the [[Universidad de Chile]].\n\nAfter the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat]] he lived as an exile in [[France]].\n\nHe published his first novel in 1999, ''Memorias prematuras'' (''Premature memoirs''), called \"a book where the writer narrates his life; the exile with his family in France, his return to Chile, his failure with women, his first dabblings in journalism and university life\" and \"for many, the best he has ever written\".<ref>[http://www.zona.cl/autor/archivo_autor.asp?IdAutor=%7B91317125-ACDC-446D-9A20-162F73BD4E72%7D&IdNoticia=%7BE44588BE-2B5C-4301-AAD4-0DA5F2D65523%7D Antonio D\u00edaz Oliva. ''Gumucio paga''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100408080150/http://www.zona.cl/autor/archivo_autor.asp?IdAutor=%7B91317125-ACDC-446D-9A20-162F73BD4E72%7D&IdNoticia=%7BE44588BE-2B5C-4301-AAD4-0DA5F2D65523%7D |date=2010-04-08 }}, ''Zona de Contacto''; kast accessed on 30.03.2012</ref>\n\nHe resided nearly four years in [[Spain]] and in 2004 he published his first novel, ''los platos rotos'' (''The broken dishes''), on which Gumucio has stated \"it is very fictional non-fiction. It is an historical essay that has something of short story, theatre, novel, narrative\".<ref>[http://rie.cl/lanacioncl/?a=22760 Juan Sharpe. ''Mi lugar es Chile''], ''[[La Naci\u00f3n (Chile)|La Naci\u00f3n]]'', 14.08.2004; last accessed on 30.03.2012</ref>\n\nAfterwards he got married and moved to [[New York City]].<ref>[http://homepages.nyu.edu/~pdn200/news/EM20050618.pdf ''50 l\u00edderes consagrados''], revista ''El S\u00e1bado'' de ''[[El Mercurio]]'', 18.06.2005, from the webpage of [[New York University]]; last accessed on 30.03.2012</ref> There, in the hometown of his wife kristina , with whom he has two daughters carlota preety and beatrice mas o menos, he wrote ''La deuda'' (''The debt'').<ref>[http://librocomentarios.blogspot.com/2009/04/librocomentarios-rafael-gumucio-lanzo.html Felipe Saleh. ''Rafael Gumucio Lanz\u00f3 su novela \u2018La Deuda\u2019''], ''Librocomentarios'', 16.04.2009; last accessed on 30.03.2012</ref>\n\nHe has written for the newspapers [[La Naci\u00f3n (Chile)|La Naci\u00f3n]], [[El Mercurio]], [[La Tercera]], [[El Metropolitano (Chile)|El Metropolitano]], [[Las \u00daltimas Noticias]],  [[El Pa\u00eds]], [[ABC (Spain)|ABC]] and [[New York Times]] and for the magazines [[Apsi]], [[Rock & Pop (magazine)|Rock & Pop]], ''Fibra'', of which he was founder and general editor and [[The Clinic (newspaper)|The Clinic]], of which he was also one of its founders.\n\nHe has also been conductor, script-writer and producer of television shows like ''Gato por liebre'' (Rock & Pop Televisi\u00f3n, 1995-1998) and of the absurdist humour show [[Plan Z (TV show)]], which was censored more than once.\n\nHe is director of the Instituto de Estudios Humor\u00edsticos of the [[Universidad Diego Portales]] and comedian-host of the ''Desde Zero'' show on [[Radio Zero]] with [[Patricio Fern\u00e1ndez]] and [[Claudia \u00c1lamo]].\n\n== Prizes ==\n* [[Anna Seghers-Preis]] 2004 (Alemania)\n* Runner-up of the [[Premio Altazor]] 2000 with ''Memorias Prematuras''<ref>[http://www.premioaltazor.cl/rafael-gumucio-2/ Gumucio en la p\u00e1gina del Premio Altazor] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120629152455/http://www.premioaltazor.cl/rafael-gumucio-2/ |date=2012-06-29 }}</ref>\n* Runner-up of the [[Premio Altazor]] 2003 for essays with ''Monstruos cardinales''\n\n== Works ==\n*''Invierno en la torre'', tale, 1995\n*''Memorias prematuras'', novel, 1999\n*''Monstruos cardinales'', column compilation, 2002\n*''Comedia nupcial'', novel, 2002\n*''Los platos rotos. Historia personal de Chile'',  2004\n*''P\u00e1ginas coloniales'', travel book, 2006\n*''La deuda'', novel, 2009\n*''Contra la belleza'', essay, 2010\n*''La situaci\u00f3n'', literary chronicle, 2011\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.letraslibres.com/index.php?sec=22&autor=Rafael%20Gumucio Art\u00edculos de Gumucio en ''Letras Libres'']\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gumucio, Rafael}}\n[[Category:Chilean journalists]]\n[[Category:Male journalists]]\n[[Category:Chilean educators]]\n[[Category:Chilean male writers]]\n[[Category:University of Chile alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Gumucio, Rafael -05.JPG|thumb|Gumucio in April 2015]]\n'''Rafael Gumucio Araya''' (born January 15, 1970 in [[Santiago de Chile|Santiago]]) is a [[Chilean people|Chilean]] writer and comedian.\n\n== Biography ==\n\nHe is son of the historian Rafael Luis Gumucio Rivas, grandson of the left-wing politician Rafael Agust\u00edn Gumucio, and the cousin of filmmaker and also politician [[Marco Enr\u00edquez-Ominami]]. He attended high school at the Colegio Regina Pacis in [[\u00d1u\u00f1oa]];,<ref>[http://diario.elmercurio.com/detalle/index.asp?id={8f628aa8-5b8e-486d-bf4a-ca23871d1d21} \u00d3scar Contardo. ''Las quejas del conde disl\u00e9xico''], ''[[El Mercurio]]'', 23.06.2002; last accessed on 30.03.2012</ref> graduated as a Spanish language teacher first and then as a Master in Literature at the [[Universidad de Chile]].\n\nAfter the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat]] he lived as an exile in [[France]].\n\nHe published his first novel in 1999, ''Memorias prematuras'' (''Premature memoirs''), called \"a book where the writer narrates his life; the exile with his family in France, his return to Chile, his failure with women, his first dabblings in journalism and university life\" and \"for many, the best he has ever written\".<ref>[http://www.zona.cl/autor/archivo_autor.asp?IdAutor=%7B91317125-ACDC-446D-9A20-162F73BD4E72%7D&IdNoticia=%7BE44588BE-2B5C-4301-AAD4-0DA5F2D65523%7D Antonio D\u00edaz Oliva. ''Gumucio paga''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100408080150/http://www.zona.cl/autor/archivo_autor.asp?IdAutor=%7B91317125-ACDC-446D-9A20-162F73BD4E72%7D&IdNoticia=%7BE44588BE-2B5C-4301-AAD4-0DA5F2D65523%7D |date=2010-04-08 }}, ''Zona de Contacto''; kast accessed on 30.03.2012</ref>\n\nHe resided nearly four years in [[Spain]] and in 2004 he published his first novel, ''los platos rotos'' (''The broken dishes''), on which Gumucio has stated \"it is very fictional non-fiction. It is an historical essay that has something of short story, theatre, novel, narrative\".<ref>[http://rie.cl/lanacioncl/?a=22760 Juan Sharpe. ''Mi lugar es Chile''], ''[[La Naci\u00f3n (Chile)|La Naci\u00f3n]]'', 14.08.2004; last accessed on 30.03.2012</ref>\n\nAfterwards he got married and moved to [[New York City]].<ref>[http://homepages.nyu.edu/~pdn200/news/EM20050618.pdf ''50 l\u00edderes consagrados''], revista ''El S\u00e1bado'' de ''[[El Mercurio]]'', 18.06.2005, from the webpage of [[New York University]]; last accessed on 30.03.2012</ref> There, in the hometown of his wife, with whom he has two daughters, he wrote ''La deuda'' (''The debt'').<ref>[http://librocomentarios.blogspot.com/2009/04/librocomentarios-rafael-gumucio-lanzo.html Felipe Saleh. ''Rafael Gumucio Lanz\u00f3 su novela \u2018La Deuda\u2019''], ''Librocomentarios'', 16.04.2009; last accessed on 30.03.2012</ref>\n\nHe has written for the newspapers [[La Naci\u00f3n (Chile)|La Naci\u00f3n]], [[El Mercurio]], [[La Tercera]], [[El Metropolitano (Chile)|El Metropolitano]], [[Las \u00daltimas Noticias]],  [[El Pa\u00eds]], [[ABC (Spain)|ABC]] and [[New York Times]] and for the magazines [[Apsi]], [[Rock & Pop (magazine)|Rock & Pop]], ''Fibra'', of which he was founder and general editor and [[The Clinic (newspaper)|The Clinic]], of which he was also one of its founders.\n\nHe has also been conductor, script-writer and producer of television shows like ''Gato por liebre'' (Rock & Pop Televisi\u00f3n, 1995-1998) and of the absurdist humour show [[Plan Z (TV show)]], which was censored more than once.\n\nHe is director of the Instituto de Estudios Humor\u00edsticos of the [[Universidad Diego Portales]] and comedian-host of the ''Desde Zero'' show on [[Radio Zero]] with [[Patricio Fern\u00e1ndez]] and [[Claudia \u00c1lamo]].\n\n== Prizes ==\n* [[Anna Seghers-Preis]] 2004 (Alemania)\n* Runner-up of the [[Premio Altazor]] 2000 with ''Memorias Prematuras''<ref>[http://www.premioaltazor.cl/rafael-gumucio-2/ Gumucio en la p\u00e1gina del Premio Altazor] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120629152455/http://www.premioaltazor.cl/rafael-gumucio-2/ |date=2012-06-29 }}</ref>\n* Runner-up of the [[Premio Altazor]] 2003 for essays with ''Monstruos cardinales''\n\n== Works ==\n*''Invierno en la torre'', tale, 1995\n*''Memorias prematuras'', novel, 1999\n*''Monstruos cardinales'', column compilation, 2002\n*''Comedia nupcial'', novel, 2002\n*''Los platos rotos. Historia personal de Chile'',  2004\n*''P\u00e1ginas coloniales'', travel book, 2006\n*''La deuda'', novel, 2009\n*''Contra la belleza'', essay, 2010\n*''La situaci\u00f3n'', literary chronicle, 2011\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.letraslibres.com/index.php?sec=22&autor=Rafael%20Gumucio Art\u00edculos de Gumucio en ''Letras Libres'']\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gumucio, Rafael}}\n[[Category:Chilean journalists]]\n[[Category:Male journalists]]\n[[Category:Chilean educators]]\n[[Category:Chilean male writers]]\n[[Category:University of Chile alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n", "name_user": "24.189.163.233", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rafael_Gumucio"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Moore (writer)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Stephen Moore}}\n{{Short description|American writer and economic commentator}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Stephen Moore\n|image       = Stephen Moore by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1960|2|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Winnetka, Illinois]], U.S.\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|known_for   = Founding President of the [[Club for Growth]]<br/>Member of the Editorial Board of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''<br/>Chief Economist of the [[The Heritage Foundation|Heritage Foundation]]\n|education   = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[George Mason University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n[[File:Stephen Moore speaking at Americans for Prosperity Foundation event in 2008.jpg|thumb|Stephen Moore speaking at [[Americans for Prosperity]] Foundation event in 2008]]\n[[File:Stephen Moore at the 2015 Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC) in National Harbor, Maryland.jpg|thumb| Stephen Moore at the 2015 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]]]]\n'''Stephen Moore''' (born February 16, 1960) is an American writer and television commentator on economic issues. He co-founded and served as president of the [[Club for Growth]] from 1999 to 2004. Moore is a former member of the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' editorial board. He worked at the Heritage Foundation during the period from 1983 to 1987 and again since 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heritage.org/staff/stephen-moore |title=Stephen Moore at the Heritage Foundation |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref> Moore advised Herman Cain's 2012 presidential campaign and [[Donald Trump]]'s 2016 presidential campaign.<ref name=\"berg\"/>\n\nMoore advocates tax cuts and other [[supply-side economics|supply-side policies]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/wall-street-journals-stephen-moore-joins-heritage-foundation-as-chief-economist/article/2542571|title=Wall Street Journal's Stephen Moore joins Heritage Foundation as chief economist|date=2014-01-21|work=Washington Examiner|last1=Lawler|first1=Joseph|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Moore's columns have appeared in outlets such as the ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[The Washington Times]]'', ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'' and ''[[National Review]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/section/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore Articles |website=Weekly Standard|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/author/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore Archive |website=National Review Online|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref> In 2017, he left [[Fox News Channel]] to join [[CNN]] as a senior economic analyst, leaving that position in early 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/stephen-moore-fox-news-cnn-contributor-2017-1?r=US&IR=T|title=Economist Stephen Moore jumps from Fox News to CNN|author=Oliver Darcy|date=January 30, 2017|work=Business Insider UK|accessdate=April 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/22/business/trump-federal-reserve-nomination-stephen-moore/index.html|title=Trump will nominate former campaign adviser Stephen Moore to Federal Reserve|first=Donna Borak, CNN|last=Business|website=CNN}}</ref> Along with [[Larry Kudlow]], Moore advised the Trump administration during the writing and passage of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|Tax Cuts and Jobs Act]].<ref name=\"cbs\"/>\n\nOn March 15, 2019, President Donald Trump announced that Moore would be nominated to serve as a [[Federal Reserve Board of Governors|governor]] of the [[Federal Reserve]].<ref name=\"berg\" /><ref name=\"ft\">{{cite news |last1=Politi |first1=James |last2=Sevastopulo |first2=Demetri |title=Trump to nominate Stephen Moore to Federal Reserve board |url=https://www.ft.com/content/11154bc4-4cbf-11e9-bbc9-6917dce3dc62 |accessdate=22 March 2019 |work=The Financial Times |date=22 March 2019 |location=Washington}}</ref> On May 2, 2019, Moore withdrew his name from consideration.<ref name = withdrew>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/02/politics/stephen-moore-fed-board-out/index.html|title=Stephen Moore out of Fed contention|publisher=CNN|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nMoore grew up in [[New Trier Township, Illinois]]. He attended Saints Faith Hope & Charity School in [[Winnetka, Illinois|Winnetka]] and graduated from [[New Trier High School]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.winnetkacurrent.com/Articles-c-2011-08-05-225811.114133-NT-alum-Steven-Moore-lets-thoughts-fly-at-Wall-Street-Journal.html|title=NT alum Stephen Moore lets thoughts fly at Wall Street Journal|date=August 5, 2011|publisher=Winnetka Current|last1=Henry|first1=Alan|access-date=13 August 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220223820/http://www.winnetkacurrent.com/Articles-c-2011-08-05-225811.114133-NT-alum-Steven-Moore-lets-thoughts-fly-at-Wall-Street-Journal.html|archive-date=December 20, 2013}}</ref> He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (B.A.) from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] and a [[Master of Arts]] (M.A.) in [[economics]] from [[George Mason University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.org/about/staff/m/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore|publisher=Heritage Foundation|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 1983 to 1987, Moore served as the Grover M. Hermann Fellow in Budgetary Affairs at the [[Heritage Foundation]]. In 1987, Moore was the research director of President [[Ronald Reagan]]'s Privatization Commission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.johnshopkins.edu/fas/?p=90|title=Stephen Moore|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Moore spent ten years as a fellow of the [[Cato Institute]], a [[libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]] [[think tank]].<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/realspin/2014/01/24/does-stephen-moores-appointment-indicate-a-thaw-in-heritages-stance-on-immigration-reform/|title=Does Stephen Moore's Appointment Indicate A Thaw In Heritage's Stance On Immigration Reform?|date=2014-01-24|work=Forbes|last1=Nowrasteh|first1=Alex|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"post\" /> As senior economist of the [[U.S. Congress Joint Economic Committee]] under Chairman [[Dick Armey]] of [[Texas]], Moore was said to be \"instrumental in creating the [[FairTax]] proposal\".<ref name=\"forbes\" />\n\nIn 1999, Moore co-founded the [[Club for Growth]], a group advocating tax cuts and a reduction in government spending, becoming its president.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/stephen-moore/|title=Stephen Moore Profile - CNBC|first=Stephen|last=Moore|website=www.cnbc.com}}</ref> While president of the group, Moore targeted \"[[Republican In Name Only|Republicans in Name Only]]\" whom he viewed as not aligned with his anti-tax views; he criticized Republican Senators who did not readily embrace tax cuts, including [[Arlen Specter]], [[Olympia Snowe]], and [[George Voinovich]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/10/magazine/fight-club.html|title=Fight Club|last=Bai|first=Matt|date=2003-08-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAt the Club for Growth, Moore sought to change the Republican party and in a 2003 interview said, \"We want to take over the party's fund-raising. We want it to be, in 10 years, that no one can win a Senate or a House seat without the support of the Club for Growth.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> From 2003 to 2004, the Club for Growth was the single largest fundraiser for Republican House and Senate candidates, only being outdone by the Republican party itself.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn December 2004, the Club for Growth\u2019s board voted to remove Moore as president, with his opponents within the organization upset by his criticism of [[George W. Bush|President George Bush]] and by the narrow defeat of [[Pat Toomey|Senator Pat Toomey]], who had the group\u2019s support. After Moore's departure, lawyers for the group sent letters to him and members of his new organization, the Free Enterprise Fund, threatening legal action for allegedly stealing the group's mailing list to raise funds for his new organization; Moore's partner [[Mallory Factor]] stated the list was acquired elsewhere.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/08/politics/leadership-dispute-causes-a-split-in-a-powerhouse-of-fundraising.html|title=Leadership Dispute Causes a Split in a Powerhouse of Fund-Raising for Conservative Causes|last=Kirkpatrick|first=David D.|date=2005-07-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAfter he left the Club for Growth, Moore founded the [[501(c)(4)]] Free Enterprise Fund with other former Club for Growth members including [[Arthur Laffer]] and Mallory Factor.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/08/politics/08club.html?_r=0|title=Leadership Dispute Causes a Split in a Powerhouse of Fund-Raising for Conservative Causes|last1=Kirkpatrick|first1=David|date=2005-07-08|work=New York Times|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> In 2005, Moore left the Free Enterprise Fund to serve on the editorial board of the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/08/30/AR2005083001728.html|title=Brothers in Arms, But Sisters at Odds|date=2005-08-31|work=The Washington Post|last1=Milbank|first1=Dana|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn September 19, 2005, the [[Federal Election Commission]] (FEC) filed suit against the Club For Growth, alleging that the group had failed to register as a [[political action committee]] in the 2000, 2002, and 2004 election cycles \"despite spending millions of dollars on federal campaign activity during the 2000, 2002, and 2004 election cycle.\" In 2007, the FEC and the Club for Growth agreed to settle the lawsuit, paying $350,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/politics/2007-09-05-club-for-growth_N.htm|title=Citizens Club for Growth to pay fine - USATODAY.com|website=usatoday30.usatoday.com|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nMoore joined [[Donna Arduin]]<ref>[https://talkingpointsmemo.com/news/meet-the-right-wing-consultant-who-goes-from-state-to-state-slashing-budgets Meet The Right-Wing Consultant Who Goes From State To State Slashing Budgets], ''[[Talking Points Memo]]'', Matt Shuham, July 29, 2019. Retrieved October 1, 2019.</ref> along with Laffer, in a former partnership, Arduin, Laffer & Moore Econometrics.<ref name=\"ii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.org/aboutus/person_detail.asp?id=550|title=Stephen J. Moore|publisher=Independent Institute|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nMoore advised [[Herman Cain]], a former presidential candidate and business executive, on his [[9\u20139\u20139 Plan|9-9-9 Tax Plan]] for his [[Herman Cain 2012 presidential campaign|2012 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"berg\" />\n\nIn 2014, the [[Heritage Foundation]] announced that Moore would rejoin the think tank as chief economist.<ref name=\"foundry\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.heritage.org/2014/01/21/stephen-moore-join-heritage-chief-economist/|title=WSJ's Stephen Moore to Join Heritage as Chief Economist|last=Bluey|first=Rob |work=The Foundry|accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref> Since March 2015 his profile on the Heritage website has described him as a \"Distinguished Visiting Fellow.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315032842/http://www.heritage.org/about/staff/m/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore|date=March 15, 2015|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heritage.org/staff/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore|website=The Heritage Foundation}}</ref>\n\nMoore is a contributing editor for ''[[National Review]]''.<ref name=\"ii\" />\n\nIn May 2015, Moore co-founded the Committee to Unleash American Prosperity with Laffer, [[Larry Kudlow]], and [[Steve Forbes]], to attempt to persuade Democratic and Republican politicians running for president to focus on fighting against \"slow growth and stagnant incomes\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.investors.com/next-president-needs-to-focus-on-economic-growth-incomes/|title=Nation's Top Challenge: Beating Slow Growth, Flat Incomes|date=2015-03-02|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moore joined 32 Advisors, an economic advisory firm.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/former-trump-senior-economic-adviser-stephen-moore-joins-32-advisors-as-a-strategic-partner-300404155.html|title=Former Trump Senior Economic Adviser Stephen Moore joins 32 Advisors as a Strategic Partner|publisher=32 Advisors|date=February 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moore worked with [[Larry Kudlow]] on overhauling the US tax policy for the Trump administration, which was eventually passed into law by Congress.<ref name=\"cbs\">{{cite news |title=Trump to nominate conservative economist Stephen Moore to Federal Reserve board |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-to-nominate-conservative-economist-stephen-moore-to-federal-reserve-board/ |accessdate=24 March 2019 |work=CBS News |agency=AP |date=22 March 2019}}</ref> In 2019, Moore was listed as the 32nd most powerful person in global finance by ''[[Worth (magazine)|Worth Magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worth.com/the-power-100-2019/|title=The Power 100 2019|date=2019-09-17|website=Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Writings and statements==\nIn July 2008, as the Fed had for months been rapidly cutting interest rates as the economy weakened into what became the [[Great Recession]], Moore stated, \"I happen to believe we should be raising rates, not cutting them.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/economy/trump-fed-pick-stephen-moore-called-for-rate-hikes-as-the-economy-was-collapsing-in-2008|title=Trump Fed pick Stephen Moore called for rate hikes as the economy was collapsing in 2008|date=March 29, 2019|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/graph/?g=nwKk|title=Effective Federal Funds Rate|date=July 1, 1954|website=FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Moore described [[climate change]] as \"the biggest scam of the last two decades.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://cup.columbia.edu/book/the-inquisition-of-climate-science/9780231157193|title=The Inquisition of Climate Science|last=Powell|first=James Lawrence|date=2011|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=|isbn=9780231527842|location=|pages=149}}</ref> In columns and [[op-ed]]s, Moore called those with concerns about climate change \"Stalinistic\" and has accused [[climate science|climate scientists]] as being part of a global conspiracy to obtain money via research grants,<ref>Scott Waldman, [https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060130013 Trump's pick for Fed sees global conspiracy on climate], [[E&E News]] (March 27, 2019).</ref> asserting that a \"tidal wave of funding\" revealed \"a powerful financial motive for scientists to conclude that the apocalypse is upon us.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.creators.com/read/stephen-moore/12/18/follow-the-climate-change-money|last=Moore|first=Stephen|title=Follow the (Climate Change) Money|publisher=Creators Syndicate|date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> In an April 2019 interview, Moore said that the Federal Reserve should not consider the [[economic impacts of climate change]] in decision making.<ref>Scott Waldman, [https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060149871 Trump Fed pick won't consider economic effects of climate], [[E&E News]] (April 9, 2019).</ref>\n\nMoore wrote a 2014 ''Kansas City Star'' opinion piece entitled, \"What's the matter with [[Paul Krugman]]?,\" responding to Krugman's earlier opinion piece \"Charlatans, Cranks and Kansas,\" which had discussed a recent major tax cut in Kansas.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kansascity.com/opinion/readers-opinion/as-i-see-it/article685284.html|title=Stephen Moore: What's the matter with Paul Krugman? Give Kansas tax breaks time to work|date=2014-07-07|work=Wall Street Journal|last1=Moore|first1=Stephen|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/30/opinion/paul-krugman-charlatans-cranks-and-kansas.html?_r=1|title=Charlatans, Cranks and Kansas|date=2014-06-29|work=New York Times|last1=Krugman|first1=Paul|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Moore said that job creation had been superior in low-taxation states during the five years ending June 2009 following the recession. After errors were found in Moore's data, he sought to correct the errors with different data that were also incorrect. Miriam Pepper, editorial page editor for the ''Star'' stated \"I won't be running anything else from Stephen Moore.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cjr.org/united_states_project/stephen_moore_heritage_foundation_paul_krugman_kansas_city_star.php|title=Why one editor won't run any more op-eds by the Heritage Foundation's top economist|website=Columbia Journalism Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hiltzik/la-fi-mh-a-newspaper-factchecks-20140805-column.html|title=A newspaper fact-checks its own right-wing op-ed; hilarity ensues|first=Michael|last=Hiltzik|website=latimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 op-ed in the Washington Times, Moore cited the role of a \"culture of virtue\" in America\u2019s economic success, writing, \"What is irrefutable is that marriage with a devoted husband and wife in the home is a far better social program than food stamps, Medicaid, public housing or even all of them combined.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/01/business/economy/stephen-moore-divorce.html|title=Trump Fed Pick\u2019s Divorce Records Are Put Under Temporary Seal|first1=Jim|last1=Tankersley|first2=Glenn|last2=Thrush|first3=Patricia|last3=Cohen|date=April 1, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nMoore has often expressed support for some variation of a gold standard. In 2015 he declared, \"We have got to get rid of the Federal Reserve and move towards a gold standard in this country!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2019/04/16/eight-times-trump-fed-pick-stephen-moore-has-endorsed-some-version-gold-standard/223459|title=Eight times that Trump Fed pick Stephen Moore has endorsed some version of the gold standard|date=April 16, 2019|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref> Few economists support a gold standard.<ref>http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/gold-standard</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/22/us/politics/trump-herman-cain-federal-reserve.html|title=As Herman Cain Bows Out of Fed Contention, Focus Shifts to Stephen Moore|first1=Jim|last1=Tankersley|first2=Alan|last2=Rappeport|date=April 22, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring a 2016 debate on the minimum wage, Moore stated, \"I\u2019m a radical on this. I\u2019d get rid of a lot of these child labor laws. I want people starting to work at 11, 12.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/29/us/politics/stephen-moore-fed-women.html|title=White House Reviewing Stephen Moore\u2019s Writings|first=Jim|last=Tankersley|date=29 April 2019|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nMoore served as one of the top economic advisers to [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"jtankersley\">{{cite news|last1=Tankersley|first1=Jim|title=Donald Trump's new team of billionaire advisers could threaten his populist message|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/08/05/donald-trumps-economic-team-the-ultra-rich-to-the-rescue/ |accessdate=6 August 2016|publisher=Washington Post|date=5 August 2016}}</ref> Moore is known to be a strong supporter of President Trump.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-fed-moore-idUSKCN1R30E2|title=Trump taps a strident Powell critic for spot on Fed board|date=2019-03-22|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-03-23|language=en}}</ref> In 2018, Moore and Laffer wrote the book ''[[Trumponomics]]'', in which they lauded the Trump administration's economic policies<ref name=\"cbs\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|author=[[N. Gregory Mankiw]]|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/review-essay/2018-12-11/snake-oil-economics|title=Snake-Oil Economics: The Bad Math Behind Trump\u2019s Policies|work=Foreign Affairs|issue=January/February 2019|language=en-US|issn=0015-7120}}</ref> and criticized the economic performance of the [[George W. Bush]] years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/11/trumponomics-book-trump-tax-cuts-rich-deficits.html|title=Trumponomics Tries to Praise Trump, But Instead Exposes His Corruption|last=Chait|first=Jonathan|date=2018-11-28|website=Intelligencer|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Trump endorsed the book in a March 2019 tweet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/3/22/18277635/stephen-moore-nominated-to-federal-reserve-board|title=Stephen Moore, the Trump loyalist nominated to the Fed, explained|last=Rupar|first=Aaron|date=2019-03-22|website=Vox|access-date=2019-03-23}}</ref> In the book, Moore and Laffer argue that the Trump administration's 2017 tax plan would raise GDP growth rates to as much as 6% and not increase budget deficits.<ref name=\":2\" /> In a 2019 review of the book, [[N. Gregory Mankiw]], a conservative economics professor at Harvard University and head of the [[Council of Economic Advisors]] under President George W. Bush, described the book as \"snake-oil economics,\" writing that Moore and Laffer's analysis was based on \"wishful thinking\" rather than \"the foundation of professional consensus or serious studies from peer-reviewed journals.\"<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\"hill\">{{cite news |last1=Bowden |first1=John |title=Former Bush adviser: Senate should reject Stephen Moore |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/435440-former-bush-adviser-says-the-senate-should-reject-stephen-moore |work=The Hill |date=23 March 2019 |language=en |accessdate= 24 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nMoore asserted in a December 2018 appearance on CNN that the Federal Reserve was causing deflation in the economy, although Commerce Department data showed there was consistent inflation.<ref name=\"long\" /><ref name=\"vox\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/3/22/18277635/stephen-moore-nominated-to-federal-reserve-board|title=Stephen Moore, the Trump loyalist nominated to the Fed, explained|first=Aaron|last=Rupar|date=22 March 2019|website=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/graph/?g=nKEe|title=Inflation Based on Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers: All Items|date=January 1, 1947|website=FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis}}</ref> In April 2019 Moore asserted deflation was \"the whole reason the economy was so poor in late 2018,\" although inflation was 2.2% in the fourth quarter of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/440902-stephen-moore-gop-senators-shouldnt-walk-the-plank-for-me|title=Stephen Moore: GOP senators shouldn't 'walk the plank' for me|first=Sylvan|last=Lane|date=April 26, 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn September 2018, Moore wrote a ''Wall Street Journal'' opinion piece entitled, \"The Corporate Tax Cut Is Paying for Itself,\" in which he asserted that \"faster-than-expected growth has produced a revenue windfall.\" Corporate tax receipts for the fiscal year ended September 2018 were down 31% from the prior fiscal year, the largest decline since records began in 1934, except for during the [[Great Recession]] when corporate profits, and hence corporate tax receipts, plummeted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-corporate-tax-cut-is-paying-for-itself-1537310846|title=Opinion: The Corporate Tax Cut Is Paying for Itself|first=Stephen|last=Moore|date=September 18, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/03/22/with-corporate-tax-receipts-sagging-federal-deficit-hits-monthly-high/|title=Analysis: With corporate tax receipts sagging, the federal deficit hits a monthly high|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pgpf.org/blog/2018/10/corporate-tax-receipts-were-down-by-nearly-one-third-in-fiscal-year-2018|title=Corporate Tax Receipts Took an Unprecedented Drop This Year|website=www.pgpf.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itep.org/corporate-profits-up-corporate-federal-tax-collections-down/|title=Corporate Profits \ud83e\udc09, Corporate Federal Tax Collections \ud83e\udc0b|website=ITEP}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Moore stated, \"There's no bigger swamp in Washington than the Federal Reserve Board. It's filled with hundreds of economists who are worthless, who have the wrong model in their mind. They should all be, they should all be fired and they should be replaced by good economists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/438707-trumps-fed-board-nominee-has-a-history-of-radical-views-on-economy-democracy|title=Trump's Fed board nominee has a history of 'radical' views on economy, democracy: CNN|first=Tal|last=Axelrod|date=12 April 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref>\n\nBefore his nomination to the Federal Reserve Board, in late December 2018 Moore stated, while on a radio talk show, that he believed \"the people on the Federal Reserve Board should be thrown out for economic malpractice\".<ref name=\"berg\" />\n\nOn March 13, 2019, Moore co-authored a column in the ''Wall Street Journal'' which asserted that the [[Federal Reserve]]'s policies were slowing the economy and causing \"wild swings in the stock market,\" at a time the Dow was up 13% for the year. He also asserted that the Fed should focus more on commodities price changes rather than overall price changes. [[Larry Kudlow]], the Director of the U.S. [[National Economic Council (United States)|National Economic Council]], showed the article to President Trump, who decided he wanted to place Moore on the Federal Reserve Board.<ref name=\"berg\" /><ref name=\"long\" />\n\nMoore called for higher interest rates when the economy was recovering from the Great Recession under Barack Obama, but has called for lower rates when the economy has fully recovered and continues to grow under Donald Trump.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> Moore stated in August 2018, \"I have to confess: I was wrong about inflation in 2009 and 2010. I thought there would be a lot of inflation with the Fed lowering rates to practically zero, and that was wrong.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/08/22/trump-has-flipped-fed-will-conservatives-join-him/|title=Analysis &#124; Trump has flipped on the Fed. Will conservatives join him?|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, Moore referred to individuals who protested stay-at-home orders during the coronavirus pandemic as \"the modern-day Rosa Parks \u2014 they are protesting against injustice and a loss of liberties.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/rallies-against-stay-at-home-orders-grow-as-trump-sides-with-protesters/2020/04/17/1405ba54-7f4e-11ea-8013-1b6da0e4a2b7_story.html|title=Rallies against stay-at-home orders grow as Trump sides with protesters|date=2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Federal Reserve Board candidacy==\nOn March 22, 2019, Trump announced he would nominate Moore to fill one of the two vacant seats at the [[Federal Reserve Board of Governors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/22/trump-reportedly-considering-stephen-moore-for-fed-appointment.html|title=Trump says he will nominate Fed critic Stephen Moore for central bank appointment|first= Jeff|last=Cox |publisher=CNBC}}</ref><ref name=\"berg\">{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Jennifer |last2=Mohsin |first2=Saleha |last3=Talev |first3=Margaret |last4=Torres |first4=Craig |last5=Miller |first5=Rich |title=Trump Says He'll Nominate Stephen Moore to Federal Reserve Board |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-22/trump-said-to-consider-stephen-moore-for-federal-reserve-board |accessdate=22 March 2019 |work=Bloomberg}}</ref> After the nomination was announced, Moore stated \"I\u2019m kind of new to this game, frankly, so I\u2019m going to be on a steep learning curve myself about how the Fed operates, how the Federal Reserve makes it decisions, and this is a real, exciting opportunity for me.\"<ref name=\"we\">{{cite news |last1=Wilhelm |first1=Colin |title=Surprise Trump Fed pick Stephen Moore gains support of Rand Paul |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/economy/surprise-trump-fed-pick-stephen-moore-gains-support-of-rand-paul |accessdate=26 March 2019 |work=Washington Examiner |date=25 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDemocratic Senators denounced Moore as unqualified for the post, and called upon Trump to drop the nomination.<ref name=\"paletta\">{{cite news |last1=Paletta |first1=Damian |last2=Werner |first2=Erica |title=Stephen Moore edges closer to Fed seat as key GOP lawmakers express support |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/stephen-moore-edges-closer-to-fed-seat-as-key-gop-lawmakers-express-support/2019/03/26/33cd2d18-4f4d-11e9-88a1-ed346f0ec94f_story.html |accessdate=26 March 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=26 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"VettingWoes\">Alan Rappeport, Jim Tankersley & Glenn Thrush, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/28/us/politics/stephen-moore-taxes-trump.html Stephen Moore;s Unpaid Taxes Underscore Trump\u2019s Vetting Woes], ''New York Times'' (March 28, 2019).</ref> Democrats also criticized Moore over an unpaid $75,000 tax lien entered against him.<ref name=\"VettingWoes\"/> Conversely, key Republican senators expressed support for Moore's nomination, including key members of the [[Senate Banking Committee]], which considers nomination to the Fed board.<ref name=\"paletta\"/> Republican senator [[Richard Shelby]] said, \"I\u2019ve always said they could use diversity, you don\u2019t need to be a Nobel laureate or University of Chicago professor.\"<ref name=\"dow\">{{cite news |last1=Robb |first1=Greg |title=The democratization case for Stephen Moore at the Fed |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/the-democratization-case-for-stephen-moore-at-the-fed-2019-03-26 |accessdate=26 March 2019 |work=MarketWatch |publisher=[[Dow Jones & Co.]] |date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nEndorsements for Moore's nomination came from his long-time collaborator [[Larry Kudlow]], who recommended the appointment,<ref name=\"long\" /> and from Adam Brandon, president of the conservative advocacy group [[FreedomWorks]].<ref name=\"dn\">{{cite news|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2019/03/22/trump-nominate-stephen-moore-fed-board/39243253/|title=Trump to nominate Stephen Moore for Fed board|last1=Lucey|first1=Catherine|date=22 March 2019|work=Detroit News|accessdate=24 March 2019|agency=Associated Press|language=en}}</ref> Moore\u2019s former employer, ''The Wall Street Journal'' editorial board, endorsed Moore for the Fed on March 28, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/steve-moore-for-the-fed-11553816429|title=Opinion &#124; Steve Moore for the Fed|last=Board|first=The Editorial|date=March 28, 2019|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\nIn an appearance on [[Fox Business Network]], political commentator [[Charlie Gasparino]] described Steve Moore as \"the counterweight to [Chair of the Federal Reserve Jerome] Powell\u2019s hawkishness.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.foxbusiness.com/v/6022114833001/|title=Trump sees Steve Moore as a counterweight to Fed's Jerome Powell|website=Fox Business|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Journalist [[Fred Barnes (journalist)|Fred Barnes]] defended Moore from his critics, writing, \"He\u2019s a disrupter, like Trump. That\u2019s why the president likes him. And that\u2019s why Moore is what the sluggish Federal Reserve needs most of all: a fresh voice who argues loudly for faster growth and thus better times in America.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/columnists/moore-gets-the-kavanaugh-treatment|title=Moore gets the Kavanaugh treatment|date=2019-04-05|website=Washington Examiner|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nThe nomination stirred immediate criticism by economists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2viSCWo|title=Reagan\u2019s Supply-Side Warriors Blaze a Comeback Under Trump|last=Schreckinger|first=Ben|website=POLITICO Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"berg\" /><ref name=\"dn\" /> and was widely viewed as the most political appointment to the Federal Reserve Board since the 1980s.<ref name=\"long\">{{cite news |last1=Long |first1=Heather |title=Trump picks close ally Stephen Moore for Fed seat as economy shows signs of weakness |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/03/22/trump-picks-close-ally-stephen-moore-fed-seat-economy-shows-signs-weakness/ |accessdate=24 March 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=22 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/06/upshot/fed-moore-cain-risk-partisanship.html|title=What\u2019s at Risk if the Fed Becomes as Partisan as the Rest of Washington|last=Irwin|first=Neil|date=2019-04-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Benn Steil]], director of international economics for the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], stated he found the decision appalling.<ref name=\"ft\" /> Monetary economist [[George Selgin]] stated he believed Moore was unfit to serve on the Board.<ref name=\":1\" /> Economist [[Justin Wolfers]] called the selection of Moore \"the first genuinely bad Trump pick for the Fed\" and called on the Senate not to confirm Moore.<ref name=\"long\" /> [[Harvard University|Harvard]] economics professor [[Greg Mankiw]] said that Moore \"does not have the intellectual gravitas\" for the position.<ref name=\"murray\">{{cite news |title=Swift Pushback on Stephen Moore, Trump's Latest Pick for the Fed | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-24/swift-pushback-on-stephen-moore-trump-s-latest-pick-for-the-fed | accessdate=26 March 2019 |work=Bloomberg |date=25 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/mar/30/trump-stephen-moore-federal-reserve-board|title=Trump Fed pick was held in contempt for failing to pay ex-wife over $300,000|author=Jon Swaine & David Smith|date=March 30, 2019|work=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2019, 105 professors, former government officials and analysts signed a one-sentence letter expressing \"support\" for Moore's candidacy for the Federal Reserve Board. Signatories included [[Steve Forbes]], [[Edwin Feulner|Ed Feulner]], and Bill Ford, the former President of the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/438971-more-than-100-economists-activists-back-stephen-moore-for-fed|title=More than 100 economists, activists back Stephen Moore for Federal Reserve|first=Sylvan|last=Lane|date=15 April 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref>\n\nEconomist Menzie Chinn noted that Moore has not authored or co-authored any peer-reviewed journal articles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://econbrowser.com/archives/2019/03/update-mr-stephen-moores-peer-reviewed-journal-articles|title=Update: Mr. Stephen Moore\u2019s Peer Reviewed Journal Articles - Econbrowser|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, CNN and ''The New York Times'' reported on several articles Moore had written in the ''[[National Review]]'' in the early 2000s that denigrated women, which Moore dismissed as spoofs or jokes. ''The Times'' reported, \"Congressional Republicans say [Moore's views on interest rates and the gold standard] are less likely to impede Mr. Moore\u2019s confirmation prospects than concerns over his personal life and past statements.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/22/politics/stephen-moore-federal-reserve-kfile/index.html|title=Trump Fed pick Stephen Moore called it a 'travesty' that women 'feel free' to play sports with men|author=Andrew Kaczynski and Paul LeBlanc|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/22/us/politics/trump-herman-cain-federal-reserve.html|title=As Herman Cain Bows Out of Fed Contention, Focus Shifts to Stephen Moore|first1=Jim|last1=Tankersley|first2=Alan|last2=Rappeport|date=22 April 2019|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn May 2, 2019, Moore withdrew his name from consideration, saying \"The unrelenting attacks on my character have become untenable for me and my family and 3 more months of this would be too hard on us.\" Following his withdrawal, Moore penned an op-ed in the [[The Wall Street Journal|''Wall Street Journal'']] where he decried his critics, writing, \"What did me in was not my economic ideas but gutter campaign tactics and personal assaults.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/my-brush-with-personal-destruction-11556837664|title=Opinion {{!}} My Brush With Personal Destruction|last=Moore|first=Stephen|date=2019-05-02|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-05-20|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Some Senate Republicans expressed relief that they would not have to cast a vote for or against him, because of his history of remarks deprecating women as well as a concern that he would not be independent of the White House.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5582230/stephen-moore-federal-reserve-withdraws/|title=Republicans Quietly Relieved After Stephen Moore Withdraws From Federal Reserve Nomination|last=Elliott|first=Philip|date=May 2, 2019|work=Time|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMoore's call on the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates was also controversial. While supported by President Trump, it was opposed by Fed chairman Jerome Powell and other policymakers at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/27/likely-fed-nominee-stephen-moore-thinks-rates-should-be-cut-by-half-a-percentage-point.html|title=Likely Fed nominee Stephen Moore thinks rates should be cut by half a percentage point|last=Cox|first=Jeff|date=2019-03-27|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> The Federal Reserve later lowered rates by a quarter of a percent in September 2019 and again the next month. Moore reacted by calling it \u201can example of where I was right, and where my critics were wrong.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/stephen-moore-says-feds-pivot-validates-criticism-of-interest-rate-increases-11553544172|title=Stephen Moore Says Fed\u2019s Pivot Validates Criticism of Interest-Rate Increases|last=Davidson|first=Nick Timiraos and Kate|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n\nAfter having his nomination withdrawn, Moore returned to his previous positions with FreedomWorks, The Heritage Foundation, and Committee to Unleash Prosperity. Additionally, Moore became chief economic officer of Frax, a cryptocurrency that has branded itself, \"the world\u2019s decentralized central bank.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/exclusive-stephen-moore-fed-crypto-central-bank|title=EXCLUSIVE: After Stephen Moore's failed Fed bid, he's creating a crypto central bank|last=Moynihan|first=Lydia|date=2019-06-24|website=FOXBusiness|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMoore was married to Allison Moore until 2011.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 2012, a [[Virginia]] court held Moore in [[contempt of court]] for failing to pay his ex-wife $300,000 in spousal support, child support and other obligations in his divorce settlement.<ref name=\":3\" /> Moore did not respond to repeated court requests to make payments and failed to appear for a deposition before the court threatened to have him arrested and ordered him to sell his home to make the payments; the court revoked the order at Moore\u2019s request after he made a $217,000 payment.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/01/business/economy/stephen-moore-divorce.html|title=Trump Fed Pick\u2019s Divorce Records Are Put Under Temporary Seal|first1=Jim|last1=Tankersley|first2=Glenn|last2=Thrush|first3=Patricia|last3=Cohen|date=1 April 2019|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/02/trumps-federal-reserve-nominee-stephen-moores-messy-divorce.html|title=Trump's Federal Reserve nominee Stephen Moore's messy divorce|first=Dan Mangan, Brian|last=Schwartz|date=April 2, 2019|website=www.cnbc.com}}</ref> In January 2018, the [[Internal Revenue Service|IRS]] obtained a [[tax lien]] against Moore for $75,328 in unpaid federal taxes, interest and penalties, alleging Moore had filed a \"fraudulent\" tax return in 2014. Moore contended that his accountant made an error in improperly deducting child support payments and that the lien was the result of an IRS miscalculation,<ref name=\"VettingWoes\"/> though Moore claims to have paid the lien and Montgomery County, Maryland Circuit Court records show the case is closed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/moore-hopeful-for-fed-post-but-says-he-would-bow-out-if-he-becomes-liability-11556143736|title=Moore Hopeful for Fed Post, but Says He Would Bow Out If He Becomes Liability|last=Kiernan|first=Paul|date=2019-04-24|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-05-20|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In addition to the child support payments, the IRS also disallowed other deductions Moore had claimed.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> He has been consistently wrong about predictions for years. \n\nMoore has three sons<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/stephen-moore-who-once-ran-a-political-group-fined-350000-wants-to-take-the-fed-in-a-direction-trump-supports/2019/03/28/889396f2-509c-11e9-a3f7-78b7525a8d5f_story.html|title=Stephen Moore, who once ran a political group fined $350,000, wants to take the Fed in a direction Trump supports|website=Washington Post}}</ref> and as of 2019, is married to Anne Carey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-fed-pick-stephen-moore-owes-over-75-000-in-unpaid-taxes-11553729491|title=Trump Fed Pick Stephen Moore Owes Over $75,000 in Unpaid Taxes|first=Nick|last=Timiraos|date=March 27, 2019|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n== Selected bibliography ==\n*''Trumponomics: Inside the America First Plan to Revive Our Economy,'' with [[Arthur Laffer|Arthur B. Laffer]]. (All Points Books, 2018) {{ISBN|9781250193711}}\n*''Crash Landing: How Bush, Bernanke, Pelosi and Obama Have Wrecked the U. S. Economy (And How To Salvage America's Future)(Audio CD)''(Blackstone Audio, 2014) {{ISBN|1482923874}}\n*''The End of Prosperity'' with [[Arthur Laffer|Arthur B. Laffer]] and Peter Tanous ([[Threshold Editions]], 2008) {{ISBN|1-4165-9238-5}}\n*''Bullish On Bush: How George Bush's Ownership Society Will Make America Stronger'' (Madison Books, 2004) {{ISBN|1-56833-261-0}}\n*''It's Getting Better All the Time: 100 Greatest Trends of the Last 100 Years'' with [[Julian L. Simon]] (Cato Institute, 2000) {{ISBN|1-882577-97-3}}\n*(editor) ''Restoring the Dream: What House Republicans Plan to Do Now to Strengthen the Family, Balance the Budget, and Replace Welfare'' (Times Mirror, 1995).\n*''Still an Open Door? U.S. Immigration Policy and the American Economy'' (American University Press, 1994)\n* ''Privatization: A Strategy for Taming the Deficit'' (The Heritage Foundation, 1988)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{C-SPAN|stephenmoore}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-npo}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the [[Club for Growth]]|years=1999\u20132004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pat Toomey]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Stephen}}\n\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:George Mason University alumni]]\n[[Category:Libertarian economists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Supply-side economists]]\n[[Category:The Heritage Foundation]]\n[[Category:The Wall Street Journal people]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Illinois Republicans]]\n[[Category:New Trier High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Stephen Moore}}\n{{Short description|American writer and economic commentator}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Stephen Moore\n|image       = Stephen Moore by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1960|2|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Winnetka, Illinois]], U.S.\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|known_for   = Founding President of the [[Club for Growth]]<br/>Member of the Editorial Board of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''<br/>Chief Economist of the [[The Heritage Foundation|Heritage Foundation]]\n|education   = [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[George Mason University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n[[File:Stephen Moore speaking at Americans for Prosperity Foundation event in 2008.jpg|thumb|Stephen Moore speaking at [[Americans for Prosperity]] Foundation event in 2008]]\n[[File:Stephen Moore at the 2015 Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC) in National Harbor, Maryland.jpg|thumb| Stephen Moore at the 2015 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]]]]\n'''Stephen Moore''' (born February 16, 1960) is an American writer and television commentator on economic issues. He co-founded and served as president of the [[Club for Growth]] from 1999 to 2004. Moore is a former member of the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' editorial board. He worked at the Heritage Foundation during the period from 1983 to 1987 and again since 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heritage.org/staff/stephen-moore |title=Stephen Moore at the Heritage Foundation |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref> Moore advised Herman Cain's 2012 presidential campaign and [[Donald Trump]]'s 2016 presidential campaign.<ref name=\"berg\"/>\n\nMoore advocates tax cuts and other [[supply-side economics|supply-side policies]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/wall-street-journals-stephen-moore-joins-heritage-foundation-as-chief-economist/article/2542571|title=Wall Street Journal's Stephen Moore joins Heritage Foundation as chief economist|date=2014-01-21|work=Washington Examiner|last1=Lawler|first1=Joseph|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Moore's columns have appeared in outlets such as the ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[The Washington Times]]'', ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'' and ''[[National Review]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weeklystandard.com/section/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore Articles |website=Weekly Standard|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/author/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore Archive |website=National Review Online|access-date=2016-05-31}}</ref> In 2017, he left [[Fox News Channel]] to join [[CNN]] as a senior economic analyst, leaving that position in early 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/stephen-moore-fox-news-cnn-contributor-2017-1?r=US&IR=T|title=Economist Stephen Moore jumps from Fox News to CNN|author=Oliver Darcy|date=January 30, 2017|work=Business Insider UK|accessdate=April 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/22/business/trump-federal-reserve-nomination-stephen-moore/index.html|title=Trump will nominate former campaign adviser Stephen Moore to Federal Reserve|first=Donna Borak, CNN|last=Business|website=CNN}}</ref> Along with [[Larry Kudlow]], Moore advised the Trump administration during the writing and passage of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|Tax Cuts and Jobs Act]].<ref name=\"cbs\"/>\n\nOn March 15, 2019, President Donald Trump announced that Moore would be nominated to serve as a [[Federal Reserve Board of Governors|governor]] of the [[Federal Reserve]].<ref name=\"berg\" /><ref name=\"ft\">{{cite news |last1=Politi |first1=James |last2=Sevastopulo |first2=Demetri |title=Trump to nominate Stephen Moore to Federal Reserve board |url=https://www.ft.com/content/11154bc4-4cbf-11e9-bbc9-6917dce3dc62 |accessdate=22 March 2019 |work=The Financial Times |date=22 March 2019 |location=Washington}}</ref> On May 2, 2019, Moore withdrew his name from consideration.<ref name = withdrew>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/02/politics/stephen-moore-fed-board-out/index.html|title=Stephen Moore out of Fed contention|publisher=CNN|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nMoore grew up in [[New Trier Township, Illinois]]. He attended Saints Faith Hope & Charity School in [[Winnetka, Illinois|Winnetka]] and graduated from [[New Trier High School]] in 1978.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.winnetkacurrent.com/Articles-c-2011-08-05-225811.114133-NT-alum-Steven-Moore-lets-thoughts-fly-at-Wall-Street-Journal.html|title=NT alum Stephen Moore lets thoughts fly at Wall Street Journal|date=August 5, 2011|publisher=Winnetka Current|last1=Henry|first1=Alan|access-date=13 August 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220223820/http://www.winnetkacurrent.com/Articles-c-2011-08-05-225811.114133-NT-alum-Steven-Moore-lets-thoughts-fly-at-Wall-Street-Journal.html|archive-date=December 20, 2013}}</ref> He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (B.A.) from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] and a [[Master of Arts]] (M.A.) in [[economics]] from [[George Mason University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.org/about/staff/m/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore|publisher=Heritage Foundation|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 1983 to 1987, Moore served as the Grover M. Hermann Fellow in Budgetary Affairs at the [[Heritage Foundation]]. In 1987, Moore was the research director of President [[Ronald Reagan]]'s Privatization Commission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.johnshopkins.edu/fas/?p=90|title=Stephen Moore|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Moore spent ten years as a fellow of the [[Cato Institute]], a [[libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]] [[think tank]].<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/realspin/2014/01/24/does-stephen-moores-appointment-indicate-a-thaw-in-heritages-stance-on-immigration-reform/|title=Does Stephen Moore's Appointment Indicate A Thaw In Heritage's Stance On Immigration Reform?|date=2014-01-24|work=Forbes|last1=Nowrasteh|first1=Alex|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"post\" /> As senior economist of the [[U.S. Congress Joint Economic Committee]] under Chairman [[Dick Armey]] of [[Texas]], Moore was said to be \"instrumental in creating the [[FairTax]] proposal\".<ref name=\"forbes\" />\n\nIn 1999, Moore co-founded the [[Club for Growth]], a group advocating tax cuts and a reduction in government spending, becoming its president.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/stephen-moore/|title=Stephen Moore Profile - CNBC|first=Stephen|last=Moore|website=www.cnbc.com}}</ref> While president of the group, Moore targeted \"[[Republican In Name Only|Republicans in Name Only]]\" whom he viewed as not aligned with his anti-tax views; he criticized Republican Senators who did not readily embrace tax cuts, including [[Arlen Specter]], [[Olympia Snowe]], and [[George Voinovich]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/10/magazine/fight-club.html|title=Fight Club|last=Bai|first=Matt|date=2003-08-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAt the Club for Growth, Moore sought to change the Republican party and in a 2003 interview said, \"We want to take over the party's fund-raising. We want it to be, in 10 years, that no one can win a Senate or a House seat without the support of the Club for Growth.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> From 2003 to 2004, the Club for Growth was the single largest fundraiser for Republican House and Senate candidates, only being outdone by the Republican party itself.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn December 2004, the Club for Growth\u2019s board voted to remove Moore as president, with his opponents within the organization upset by his criticism of [[George W. Bush|President George Bush]] and by the narrow defeat of [[Pat Toomey|Senator Pat Toomey]], who had the group\u2019s support. After Moore's departure, lawyers for the group sent letters to him and members of his new organization, the Free Enterprise Fund, threatening legal action for allegedly stealing the group's mailing list to raise funds for his new organization; Moore's partner [[Mallory Factor]] stated the list was acquired elsewhere.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/08/politics/leadership-dispute-causes-a-split-in-a-powerhouse-of-fundraising.html|title=Leadership Dispute Causes a Split in a Powerhouse of Fund-Raising for Conservative Causes|last=Kirkpatrick|first=David D.|date=2005-07-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAfter he left the Club for Growth, Moore founded the [[501(c)(4)]] Free Enterprise Fund with other former Club for Growth members including [[Arthur Laffer]] and Mallory Factor.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/08/politics/08club.html?_r=0|title=Leadership Dispute Causes a Split in a Powerhouse of Fund-Raising for Conservative Causes|last1=Kirkpatrick|first1=David|date=2005-07-08|work=New York Times|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> In 2005, Moore left the Free Enterprise Fund to serve on the editorial board of the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/08/30/AR2005083001728.html|title=Brothers in Arms, But Sisters at Odds|date=2005-08-31|work=The Washington Post|last1=Milbank|first1=Dana|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn September 19, 2005, the [[Federal Election Commission]] (FEC) filed suit against the Club For Growth, alleging that the group had failed to register as a [[political action committee]] in the 2000, 2002, and 2004 election cycles \"despite spending millions of dollars on federal campaign activity during the 2000, 2002, and 2004 election cycle.\" In 2007, the FEC and the Club for Growth agreed to settle the lawsuit, paying $350,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/politics/2007-09-05-club-for-growth_N.htm|title=Citizens Club for Growth to pay fine - USATODAY.com|website=usatoday30.usatoday.com|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nMoore joined [[Donna Arduin]]<ref>[https://talkingpointsmemo.com/news/meet-the-right-wing-consultant-who-goes-from-state-to-state-slashing-budgets Meet The Right-Wing Consultant Who Goes From State To State Slashing Budgets], ''[[Talking Points Memo]]'', Matt Shuham, July 29, 2019. Retrieved October 1, 2019.</ref> along with Laffer, in a former partnership, Arduin, Laffer & Moore Econometrics.<ref name=\"ii\">{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.org/aboutus/person_detail.asp?id=550|title=Stephen J. Moore|publisher=Independent Institute|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nMoore advised [[Herman Cain]], a former presidential candidate and business executive, on his [[9\u20139\u20139 Plan|9-9-9 Tax Plan]] for his [[Herman Cain 2012 presidential campaign|2012 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"berg\" />\n\nIn 2014, the [[Heritage Foundation]] announced that Moore would rejoin the think tank as chief economist.<ref name=\"foundry\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.heritage.org/2014/01/21/stephen-moore-join-heritage-chief-economist/|title=WSJ's Stephen Moore to Join Heritage as Chief Economist|last=Bluey|first=Rob |work=The Foundry|accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref> Since March 2015 his profile on the Heritage website has described him as a \"Distinguished Visiting Fellow.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315032842/http://www.heritage.org/about/staff/m/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore|date=March 15, 2015|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heritage.org/staff/stephen-moore|title=Stephen Moore|website=The Heritage Foundation}}</ref>\n\nMoore is a contributing editor for ''[[National Review]]''.<ref name=\"ii\" />\n\nIn May 2015, Moore co-founded the Committee to Unleash American Prosperity with Laffer, [[Larry Kudlow]], and [[Steve Forbes]], to attempt to persuade Democratic and Republican politicians running for president to focus on fighting against \"slow growth and stagnant incomes\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.investors.com/next-president-needs-to-focus-on-economic-growth-incomes/|title=Nation's Top Challenge: Beating Slow Growth, Flat Incomes|date=2015-03-02|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moore joined 32 Advisors, an economic advisory firm.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/former-trump-senior-economic-adviser-stephen-moore-joins-32-advisors-as-a-strategic-partner-300404155.html|title=Former Trump Senior Economic Adviser Stephen Moore joins 32 Advisors as a Strategic Partner|publisher=32 Advisors|date=February 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moore worked with [[Larry Kudlow]] on overhauling the US tax policy for the Trump administration, which was eventually passed into law by Congress.<ref name=\"cbs\">{{cite news |title=Trump to nominate conservative economist Stephen Moore to Federal Reserve board |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-to-nominate-conservative-economist-stephen-moore-to-federal-reserve-board/ |accessdate=24 March 2019 |work=CBS News |agency=AP |date=22 March 2019}}</ref> In 2019, Moore was listed as the 32nd most powerful person in global finance by ''[[Worth (magazine)|Worth Magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worth.com/the-power-100-2019/|title=The Power 100 2019|date=2019-09-17|website=Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Writings and statements==\nIn July 2008, as the Fed had for months been rapidly cutting interest rates as the economy weakened into what became the [[Great Recession]], Moore stated, \"I happen to believe we should be raising rates, not cutting them.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/economy/trump-fed-pick-stephen-moore-called-for-rate-hikes-as-the-economy-was-collapsing-in-2008|title=Trump Fed pick Stephen Moore called for rate hikes as the economy was collapsing in 2008|date=March 29, 2019|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/graph/?g=nwKk|title=Effective Federal Funds Rate|date=July 1, 1954|website=FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Moore described [[climate change]] as \"the biggest scam of the last two decades.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://cup.columbia.edu/book/the-inquisition-of-climate-science/9780231157193|title=The Inquisition of Climate Science|last=Powell|first=James Lawrence|date=2011|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=|isbn=9780231527842|location=|pages=149}}</ref> In columns and [[op-ed]]s, Moore called those with concerns about climate change \"Stalinistic\" and has accused [[climate science|climate scientists]] as being part of a global conspiracy to obtain money via research grants,<ref>Scott Waldman, [https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060130013 Trump's pick for Fed sees global conspiracy on climate], [[E&E News]] (March 27, 2019).</ref> asserting that a \"tidal wave of funding\" revealed \"a powerful financial motive for scientists to conclude that the apocalypse is upon us.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.creators.com/read/stephen-moore/12/18/follow-the-climate-change-money|last=Moore|first=Stephen|title=Follow the (Climate Change) Money|publisher=Creators Syndicate|date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> In an April 2019 interview, Moore said that the Federal Reserve should not consider the [[economic impacts of climate change]] in decision making.<ref>Scott Waldman, [https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060149871 Trump Fed pick won't consider economic effects of climate], [[E&E News]] (April 9, 2019).</ref>\n\nMoore wrote a 2014 ''Kansas City Star'' opinion piece entitled, \"What's the matter with [[Paul Krugman]]?,\" responding to Krugman's earlier opinion piece \"Charlatans, Cranks and Kansas,\" which had discussed a recent major tax cut in Kansas.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kansascity.com/opinion/readers-opinion/as-i-see-it/article685284.html|title=Stephen Moore: What's the matter with Paul Krugman? Give Kansas tax breaks time to work|date=2014-07-07|work=Wall Street Journal|last1=Moore|first1=Stephen|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/30/opinion/paul-krugman-charlatans-cranks-and-kansas.html?_r=1|title=Charlatans, Cranks and Kansas|date=2014-06-29|work=New York Times|last1=Krugman|first1=Paul|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Moore said that job creation had been superior in low-taxation states during the five years ending June 2009 following the recession. After errors were found in Moore's data, he sought to correct the errors with different data that were also incorrect. Miriam Pepper, editorial page editor for the ''Star'' stated \"I won't be running anything else from Stephen Moore.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cjr.org/united_states_project/stephen_moore_heritage_foundation_paul_krugman_kansas_city_star.php|title=Why one editor won't run any more op-eds by the Heritage Foundation's top economist|website=Columbia Journalism Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hiltzik/la-fi-mh-a-newspaper-factchecks-20140805-column.html|title=A newspaper fact-checks its own right-wing op-ed; hilarity ensues|first=Michael|last=Hiltzik|website=latimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 op-ed in the Washington Times, Moore cited the role of a \"culture of virtue\" in America\u2019s economic success, writing, \"What is irrefutable is that marriage with a devoted husband and wife in the home is a far better social program than food stamps, Medicaid, public housing or even all of them combined.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/01/business/economy/stephen-moore-divorce.html|title=Trump Fed Pick\u2019s Divorce Records Are Put Under Temporary Seal|first1=Jim|last1=Tankersley|first2=Glenn|last2=Thrush|first3=Patricia|last3=Cohen|date=April 1, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nMoore has often expressed support for some variation of a gold standard. In 2015 he declared, \"We have got to get rid of the Federal Reserve and move towards a gold standard in this country!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/blog/2019/04/16/eight-times-trump-fed-pick-stephen-moore-has-endorsed-some-version-gold-standard/223459|title=Eight times that Trump Fed pick Stephen Moore has endorsed some version of the gold standard|date=April 16, 2019|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref> Few economists support a gold standard.<ref>http://www.igmchicago.org/surveys/gold-standard</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/22/us/politics/trump-herman-cain-federal-reserve.html|title=As Herman Cain Bows Out of Fed Contention, Focus Shifts to Stephen Moore|first1=Jim|last1=Tankersley|first2=Alan|last2=Rappeport|date=April 22, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring a 2016 debate on the minimum wage, Moore stated, \"I\u2019m a radical on this. I\u2019d get rid of a lot of these child labor laws. I want people starting to work at 11, 12.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/29/us/politics/stephen-moore-fed-women.html|title=White House Reviewing Stephen Moore\u2019s Writings|first=Jim|last=Tankersley|date=29 April 2019|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nMoore served as one of the top economic advisers to [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"jtankersley\">{{cite news|last1=Tankersley|first1=Jim|title=Donald Trump's new team of billionaire advisers could threaten his populist message|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/08/05/donald-trumps-economic-team-the-ultra-rich-to-the-rescue/ |accessdate=6 August 2016|publisher=Washington Post|date=5 August 2016}}</ref> Moore is known to be a strong supporter of President Trump.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-fed-moore-idUSKCN1R30E2|title=Trump taps a strident Powell critic for spot on Fed board|date=2019-03-22|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-03-23|language=en}}</ref> In 2018, Moore and Laffer wrote the book ''[[Trumponomics]]'', in which they lauded the Trump administration's economic policies<ref name=\"cbs\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|author=[[N. Gregory Mankiw]]|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/review-essay/2018-12-11/snake-oil-economics|title=Snake-Oil Economics: The Bad Math Behind Trump\u2019s Policies|work=Foreign Affairs|issue=January/February 2019|language=en-US|issn=0015-7120}}</ref> and criticized the economic performance of the [[George W. Bush]] years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/11/trumponomics-book-trump-tax-cuts-rich-deficits.html|title=Trumponomics Tries to Praise Trump, But Instead Exposes His Corruption|last=Chait|first=Jonathan|date=2018-11-28|website=Intelligencer|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Trump endorsed the book in a March 2019 tweet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/3/22/18277635/stephen-moore-nominated-to-federal-reserve-board|title=Stephen Moore, the Trump loyalist nominated to the Fed, explained|last=Rupar|first=Aaron|date=2019-03-22|website=Vox|access-date=2019-03-23}}</ref> In the book, Moore and Laffer argue that the Trump administration's 2017 tax plan would raise GDP growth rates to as much as 6% and not increase budget deficits.<ref name=\":2\" /> In a 2019 review of the book, [[N. Gregory Mankiw]], a conservative economics professor at Harvard University and head of the [[Council of Economic Advisors]] under President George W. Bush, described the book as \"snake-oil economics,\" writing that Moore and Laffer's analysis was based on \"wishful thinking\" rather than \"the foundation of professional consensus or serious studies from peer-reviewed journals.\"<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\"hill\">{{cite news |last1=Bowden |first1=John |title=Former Bush adviser: Senate should reject Stephen Moore |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/435440-former-bush-adviser-says-the-senate-should-reject-stephen-moore |work=The Hill |date=23 March 2019 |language=en |accessdate= 24 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nMoore asserted in a December 2018 appearance on CNN that the Federal Reserve was causing deflation in the economy, although Commerce Department data showed there was consistent inflation.<ref name=\"long\" /><ref name=\"vox\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/3/22/18277635/stephen-moore-nominated-to-federal-reserve-board|title=Stephen Moore, the Trump loyalist nominated to the Fed, explained|first=Aaron|last=Rupar|date=22 March 2019|website=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/graph/?g=nKEe|title=Inflation Based on Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers: All Items|date=January 1, 1947|website=FRED, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis}}</ref> In April 2019 Moore asserted deflation was \"the whole reason the economy was so poor in late 2018,\" although inflation was 2.2% in the fourth quarter of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/440902-stephen-moore-gop-senators-shouldnt-walk-the-plank-for-me|title=Stephen Moore: GOP senators shouldn't 'walk the plank' for me|first=Sylvan|last=Lane|date=April 26, 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref><ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nIn September 2018, Moore wrote a ''Wall Street Journal'' opinion piece entitled, \"The Corporate Tax Cut Is Paying for Itself,\" in which he asserted that \"faster-than-expected growth has produced a revenue windfall.\" Corporate tax receipts for the fiscal year ended September 2018 were down 31% from the prior fiscal year, the largest decline since records began in 1934, except for during the [[Great Recession]] when corporate profits, and hence corporate tax receipts, plummeted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-corporate-tax-cut-is-paying-for-itself-1537310846|title=Opinion: The Corporate Tax Cut Is Paying for Itself|first=Stephen|last=Moore|date=September 18, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/03/22/with-corporate-tax-receipts-sagging-federal-deficit-hits-monthly-high/|title=Analysis: With corporate tax receipts sagging, the federal deficit hits a monthly high|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pgpf.org/blog/2018/10/corporate-tax-receipts-were-down-by-nearly-one-third-in-fiscal-year-2018|title=Corporate Tax Receipts Took an Unprecedented Drop This Year|website=www.pgpf.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itep.org/corporate-profits-up-corporate-federal-tax-collections-down/|title=Corporate Profits \ud83e\udc09, Corporate Federal Tax Collections \ud83e\udc0b|website=ITEP}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Moore stated, \"There's no bigger swamp in Washington than the Federal Reserve Board. It's filled with hundreds of economists who are worthless, who have the wrong model in their mind. They should all be, they should all be fired and they should be replaced by good economists.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/438707-trumps-fed-board-nominee-has-a-history-of-radical-views-on-economy-democracy|title=Trump's Fed board nominee has a history of 'radical' views on economy, democracy: CNN|first=Tal|last=Axelrod|date=12 April 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref>\n\nBefore his nomination to the Federal Reserve Board, in late December 2018 Moore stated, while on a radio talk show, that he believed \"the people on the Federal Reserve Board should be thrown out for economic malpractice\".<ref name=\"berg\" />\n\nOn March 13, 2019, Moore co-authored a column in the ''Wall Street Journal'' which asserted that the [[Federal Reserve]]'s policies were slowing the economy and causing \"wild swings in the stock market,\" at a time the Dow was up 13% for the year. He also asserted that the Fed should focus more on commodities price changes rather than overall price changes. [[Larry Kudlow]], the Director of the U.S. [[National Economic Council (United States)|National Economic Council]], showed the article to President Trump, who decided he wanted to place Moore on the Federal Reserve Board.<ref name=\"berg\" /><ref name=\"long\" />\n\nMoore called for higher interest rates when the economy was recovering from the Great Recession under Barack Obama, but has called for lower rates when the economy has fully recovered and continues to grow under Donald Trump.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> Moore stated in August 2018, \"I have to confess: I was wrong about inflation in 2009 and 2010. I thought there would be a lot of inflation with the Fed lowering rates to practically zero, and that was wrong.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/08/22/trump-has-flipped-fed-will-conservatives-join-him/|title=Analysis &#124; Trump has flipped on the Fed. Will conservatives join him?|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, Moore referred to individuals who protested stay-at-home orders during the coronavirus pandemic as \"the modern-day Rosa Parks \u2014 they are protesting against injustice and a loss of liberties.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/rallies-against-stay-at-home-orders-grow-as-trump-sides-with-protesters/2020/04/17/1405ba54-7f4e-11ea-8013-1b6da0e4a2b7_story.html|title=Rallies against stay-at-home orders grow as Trump sides with protesters|date=2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Federal Reserve Board candidacy==\nOn March 22, 2019, Trump announced he would nominate Moore to fill one of the two vacant seats at the [[Federal Reserve Board of Governors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/22/trump-reportedly-considering-stephen-moore-for-fed-appointment.html|title=Trump says he will nominate Fed critic Stephen Moore for central bank appointment|first= Jeff|last=Cox |publisher=CNBC}}</ref><ref name=\"berg\">{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Jennifer |last2=Mohsin |first2=Saleha |last3=Talev |first3=Margaret |last4=Torres |first4=Craig |last5=Miller |first5=Rich |title=Trump Says He'll Nominate Stephen Moore to Federal Reserve Board |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-22/trump-said-to-consider-stephen-moore-for-federal-reserve-board |accessdate=22 March 2019 |work=Bloomberg}}</ref> After the nomination was announced, Moore stated \"I\u2019m kind of new to this game, frankly, so I\u2019m going to be on a steep learning curve myself about how the Fed operates, how the Federal Reserve makes it decisions, and this is a real, exciting opportunity for me.\"<ref name=\"we\">{{cite news |last1=Wilhelm |first1=Colin |title=Surprise Trump Fed pick Stephen Moore gains support of Rand Paul |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/economy/surprise-trump-fed-pick-stephen-moore-gains-support-of-rand-paul |accessdate=26 March 2019 |work=Washington Examiner |date=25 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDemocratic Senators denounced Moore as unqualified for the post, and called upon Trump to drop the nomination.<ref name=\"paletta\">{{cite news |last1=Paletta |first1=Damian |last2=Werner |first2=Erica |title=Stephen Moore edges closer to Fed seat as key GOP lawmakers express support |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/stephen-moore-edges-closer-to-fed-seat-as-key-gop-lawmakers-express-support/2019/03/26/33cd2d18-4f4d-11e9-88a1-ed346f0ec94f_story.html |accessdate=26 March 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=26 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"VettingWoes\">Alan Rappeport, Jim Tankersley & Glenn Thrush, [https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/28/us/politics/stephen-moore-taxes-trump.html Stephen Moore;s Unpaid Taxes Underscore Trump\u2019s Vetting Woes], ''New York Times'' (March 28, 2019).</ref> Democrats also criticized Moore over an unpaid $75,000 tax lien entered against him.<ref name=\"VettingWoes\"/> Conversely, key Republican senators expressed support for Moore's nomination, including key members of the [[Senate Banking Committee]], which considers nomination to the Fed board.<ref name=\"paletta\"/> Republican senator [[Richard Shelby]] said, \"I\u2019ve always said they could use diversity, you don\u2019t need to be a Nobel laureate or University of Chicago professor.\"<ref name=\"dow\">{{cite news |last1=Robb |first1=Greg |title=The democratization case for Stephen Moore at the Fed |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/the-democratization-case-for-stephen-moore-at-the-fed-2019-03-26 |accessdate=26 March 2019 |work=MarketWatch |publisher=[[Dow Jones & Co.]] |date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nEndorsements for Moore's nomination came from his long-time collaborator [[Larry Kudlow]], who recommended the appointment,<ref name=\"long\" /> and from Adam Brandon, president of the conservative advocacy group [[FreedomWorks]].<ref name=\"dn\">{{cite news|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/politics/2019/03/22/trump-nominate-stephen-moore-fed-board/39243253/|title=Trump to nominate Stephen Moore for Fed board|last1=Lucey|first1=Catherine|date=22 March 2019|work=Detroit News|accessdate=24 March 2019|agency=Associated Press|language=en}}</ref> Moore\u2019s former employer, ''The Wall Street Journal'' editorial board, endorsed Moore for the Fed on March 28, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/steve-moore-for-the-fed-11553816429|title=Opinion &#124; Steve Moore for the Fed|last=Board|first=The Editorial|date=March 28, 2019|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\nIn an appearance on [[Fox Business Network]], political commentator [[Charlie Gasparino]] described Steve Moore as \"the counterweight to [Chair of the Federal Reserve Jerome] Powell\u2019s hawkishness.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.foxbusiness.com/v/6022114833001/|title=Trump sees Steve Moore as a counterweight to Fed's Jerome Powell|website=Fox Business|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> Journalist [[Fred Barnes (journalist)|Fred Barnes]] defended Moore from his critics, writing, \"He\u2019s a disrupter, like Trump. That\u2019s why the president likes him. And that\u2019s why Moore is what the sluggish Federal Reserve needs most of all: a fresh voice who argues loudly for faster growth and thus better times in America.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/columnists/moore-gets-the-kavanaugh-treatment|title=Moore gets the Kavanaugh treatment|date=2019-04-05|website=Washington Examiner|language=en|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nThe nomination stirred immediate criticism by economists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2viSCWo|title=Reagan\u2019s Supply-Side Warriors Blaze a Comeback Under Trump|last=Schreckinger|first=Ben|website=POLITICO Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"berg\" /><ref name=\"dn\" /> and was widely viewed as the most political appointment to the Federal Reserve Board since the 1980s.<ref name=\"long\">{{cite news |last1=Long |first1=Heather |title=Trump picks close ally Stephen Moore for Fed seat as economy shows signs of weakness |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/03/22/trump-picks-close-ally-stephen-moore-fed-seat-economy-shows-signs-weakness/ |accessdate=24 March 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=22 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/06/upshot/fed-moore-cain-risk-partisanship.html|title=What\u2019s at Risk if the Fed Becomes as Partisan as the Rest of Washington|last=Irwin|first=Neil|date=2019-04-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-04-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Benn Steil]], director of international economics for the [[Council on Foreign Relations]], stated he found the decision appalling.<ref name=\"ft\" /> Monetary economist [[George Selgin]] stated he believed Moore was unfit to serve on the Board.<ref name=\":1\" /> Economist [[Justin Wolfers]] called the selection of Moore \"the first genuinely bad Trump pick for the Fed\" and called on the Senate not to confirm Moore.<ref name=\"long\" /> [[Harvard University|Harvard]] economics professor [[Greg Mankiw]] said that Moore \"does not have the intellectual gravitas\" for the position.<ref name=\"murray\">{{cite news |title=Swift Pushback on Stephen Moore, Trump's Latest Pick for the Fed | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-24/swift-pushback-on-stephen-moore-trump-s-latest-pick-for-the-fed | accessdate=26 March 2019 |work=Bloomberg |date=25 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/mar/30/trump-stephen-moore-federal-reserve-board|title=Trump Fed pick was held in contempt for failing to pay ex-wife over $300,000|author=Jon Swaine & David Smith|date=March 30, 2019|work=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2019, 105 professors, former government officials and analysts signed a one-sentence letter expressing \"support\" for Moore's candidacy for the Federal Reserve Board. Signatories included [[Steve Forbes]], [[Edwin Feulner|Ed Feulner]], and Bill Ford, the former President of the [[Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/438971-more-than-100-economists-activists-back-stephen-moore-for-fed|title=More than 100 economists, activists back Stephen Moore for Federal Reserve|first=Sylvan|last=Lane|date=15 April 2019|website=TheHill}}</ref>\n\nEconomist Menzie Chinn noted that Moore has not authored or co-authored any peer-reviewed journal articles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://econbrowser.com/archives/2019/03/update-mr-stephen-moores-peer-reviewed-journal-articles|title=Update: Mr. Stephen Moore\u2019s Peer Reviewed Journal Articles - Econbrowser|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, CNN and ''The New York Times'' reported on several articles Moore had written in the ''[[National Review]]'' in the early 2000s that denigrated women, which Moore dismissed as spoofs or jokes. ''The Times'' reported, \"Congressional Republicans say [Moore's views on interest rates and the gold standard] are less likely to impede Mr. Moore\u2019s confirmation prospects than concerns over his personal life and past statements.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/22/politics/stephen-moore-federal-reserve-kfile/index.html|title=Trump Fed pick Stephen Moore called it a 'travesty' that women 'feel free' to play sports with men|author=Andrew Kaczynski and Paul LeBlanc|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/22/us/politics/trump-herman-cain-federal-reserve.html|title=As Herman Cain Bows Out of Fed Contention, Focus Shifts to Stephen Moore|first1=Jim|last1=Tankersley|first2=Alan|last2=Rappeport|date=22 April 2019|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn May 2, 2019, Moore withdrew his name from consideration, saying \"The unrelenting attacks on my character have become untenable for me and my family and 3 more months of this would be too hard on us.\" Following his withdrawal, Moore penned an op-ed in the [[The Wall Street Journal|''Wall Street Journal'']] where he decried his critics, writing, \"What did me in was not my economic ideas but gutter campaign tactics and personal assaults.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/my-brush-with-personal-destruction-11556837664|title=Opinion {{!}} My Brush With Personal Destruction|last=Moore|first=Stephen|date=2019-05-02|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-05-20|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Some Senate Republicans expressed relief that they would not have to cast a vote for or against him, because of his history of remarks deprecating women as well as a concern that he would not be independent of the White House.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5582230/stephen-moore-federal-reserve-withdraws/|title=Republicans Quietly Relieved After Stephen Moore Withdraws From Federal Reserve Nomination|last=Elliott|first=Philip|date=May 2, 2019|work=Time|accessdate=2 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMoore's call on the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates was also controversial. While supported by President Trump, it was opposed by Fed chairman Jerome Powell and other policymakers at the time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/27/likely-fed-nominee-stephen-moore-thinks-rates-should-be-cut-by-half-a-percentage-point.html|title=Likely Fed nominee Stephen Moore thinks rates should be cut by half a percentage point|last=Cox|first=Jeff|date=2019-03-27|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref> The Federal Reserve later lowered rates by a quarter of a percent in September 2019 and again the next month. Moore reacted by calling it \u201can example of where I was right, and where my critics were wrong.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/stephen-moore-says-feds-pivot-validates-criticism-of-interest-rate-increases-11553544172|title=Stephen Moore Says Fed\u2019s Pivot Validates Criticism of Interest-Rate Increases|last=Davidson|first=Nick Timiraos and Kate|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>\n\nAfter having his nomination withdrawn, Moore returned to his previous positions with FreedomWorks, The Heritage Foundation, and Committee to Unleash Prosperity. Additionally, Moore became chief economic officer of Frax, a cryptocurrency that has branded itself, \"the world\u2019s decentralized central bank.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/exclusive-stephen-moore-fed-crypto-central-bank|title=EXCLUSIVE: After Stephen Moore's failed Fed bid, he's creating a crypto central bank|last=Moynihan|first=Lydia|date=2019-06-24|website=FOXBusiness|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMoore was married to Allison Moore until 2011.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 2012, a [[Virginia]] court held Moore in [[contempt of court]] for failing to pay his ex-wife $300,000 in spousal support, child support and other obligations in his divorce settlement.<ref name=\":3\" /> Moore did not respond to repeated court requests to make payments and failed to appear for a deposition before the court threatened to have him arrested and ordered him to sell his home to make the payments; the court revoked the order at Moore\u2019s request after he made a $217,000 payment.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/01/business/economy/stephen-moore-divorce.html|title=Trump Fed Pick\u2019s Divorce Records Are Put Under Temporary Seal|first1=Jim|last1=Tankersley|first2=Glenn|last2=Thrush|first3=Patricia|last3=Cohen|date=1 April 2019|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/02/trumps-federal-reserve-nominee-stephen-moores-messy-divorce.html|title=Trump's Federal Reserve nominee Stephen Moore's messy divorce|first=Dan Mangan, Brian|last=Schwartz|date=April 2, 2019|website=www.cnbc.com}}</ref> In January 2018, the [[Internal Revenue Service|IRS]] obtained a [[tax lien]] against Moore for $75,328 in unpaid federal taxes, interest and penalties, alleging Moore had filed a \"fraudulent\" tax return in 2014. Moore contended that his accountant made an error in improperly deducting child support payments and that the lien was the result of an IRS miscalculation,<ref name=\"VettingWoes\"/> though Moore claims to have paid the lien and Montgomery County, Maryland Circuit Court records show the case is closed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/moore-hopeful-for-fed-post-but-says-he-would-bow-out-if-he-becomes-liability-11556143736|title=Moore Hopeful for Fed Post, but Says He Would Bow Out If He Becomes Liability|last=Kiernan|first=Paul|date=2019-04-24|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-05-20|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> In addition to the child support payments, the IRS also disallowed other deductions Moore had claimed.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nMoore has three sons<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/stephen-moore-who-once-ran-a-political-group-fined-350000-wants-to-take-the-fed-in-a-direction-trump-supports/2019/03/28/889396f2-509c-11e9-a3f7-78b7525a8d5f_story.html|title=Stephen Moore, who once ran a political group fined $350,000, wants to take the Fed in a direction Trump supports|website=Washington Post}}</ref> and as of 2019, is married to Anne Carey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-fed-pick-stephen-moore-owes-over-75-000-in-unpaid-taxes-11553729491|title=Trump Fed Pick Stephen Moore Owes Over $75,000 in Unpaid Taxes|first=Nick|last=Timiraos|date=March 27, 2019|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\n== Selected bibliography ==\n*''Trumponomics: Inside the America First Plan to Revive Our Economy,'' with [[Arthur Laffer|Arthur B. Laffer]]. (All Points Books, 2018) {{ISBN|9781250193711}}\n*''Crash Landing: How Bush, Bernanke, Pelosi and Obama Have Wrecked the U. S. Economy (And How To Salvage America's Future)(Audio CD)''(Blackstone Audio, 2014) {{ISBN|1482923874}}\n*''The End of Prosperity'' with [[Arthur Laffer|Arthur B. Laffer]] and Peter Tanous ([[Threshold Editions]], 2008) {{ISBN|1-4165-9238-5}}\n*''Bullish On Bush: How George Bush's Ownership Society Will Make America Stronger'' (Madison Books, 2004) {{ISBN|1-56833-261-0}}\n*''It's Getting Better All the Time: 100 Greatest Trends of the Last 100 Years'' with [[Julian L. Simon]] (Cato Institute, 2000) {{ISBN|1-882577-97-3}}\n*(editor) ''Restoring the Dream: What House Republicans Plan to Do Now to Strengthen the Family, Balance the Budget, and Replace Welfare'' (Times Mirror, 1995).\n*''Still an Open Door? U.S. Immigration Policy and the American Economy'' (American University Press, 1994)\n* ''Privatization: A Strategy for Taming the Deficit'' (The Heritage Foundation, 1988)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{C-SPAN|stephenmoore}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-npo}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the [[Club for Growth]]|years=1999\u20132004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pat Toomey]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Stephen}}\n\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:George Mason University alumni]]\n[[Category:Libertarian economists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Supply-side economists]]\n[[Category:The Heritage Foundation]]\n[[Category:The Wall Street Journal people]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Illinois Republicans]]\n[[Category:New Trier High School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "2605:a000:bfc0:28:5c5a:ee97:4c93:1c51", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Moore_(writer)"}
